This requirement specifies a system feature (provide a shopping cart during online purchase), which is a functional requirement. It does not mention availability, security, performance, usability, or other quality attributes.
Specifies a user-facing capability (printing invoices), which is a functional requirement. No quality constraints (performance, security, availability, etc.) are mentioned.

This specifies a system behavior (display detailed invoice upon order confirmation), which is a functional requirement. No non-functional qualities (performance, security, usability, etc.) are mentioned.
This specifies a functional behavior (sending an order confirmation via email). It does not state non-functional constraints (availability, security, performance, operability, etc.).

Specifies a required data element and that the system shall maintain customer email information as part of the customer profile — this is a functional requirement about data management, with no explicit non-functional constraints.
This is a functional requirement specifying that the system must display FAQs on user request; it does not specify any quality attributes (availability, performance, security, UI style, etc.).
This requirement specifies a functional capability (adding/removing products in cart). It does not mention availability, performance, usability, security, or other non-functional concerns.
This requirement specifies a functional capability (allowing a user to enter a contact number). It does not state availability, performance, security, usability, or other non-functional concerns.

This requirement specifies a functional behavior: the system must display customer support contact numbers on the screen. It does not state availability, performance, security, UI aesthetics beyond content, or other non-functional aspects.
Specifies a system capability (allow user to enter customer and product information) which is a functional requirement. No quality attributes (availability, security, usability, etc.) are mentioned.

This is a functional requirement specifying that the system must provide the capability for a user to select a support type. It does not explicitly state non-functional concerns such as usability, performance, security, etc.
Specifies a user-facing capability (register for newsletters/surveys in profile), i.e., functional behavior. No quality attributes (performance, security, usability, etc.) are mentioned.

This requirement specifies a visible system behavior—displaying user-specific frequently searched items—so it is a functional requirement. It does not mention availability, performance, security, usability, or other quality attributes.

This requirement specifies a system behavior (displaying detailed information about a selected order), which is functional. It does not mention availability, performance, security, UI aesthetics, or other quality attributes.

This is a functional requirement specifying that the system shall display online help on user request. It does not explicitly state non-functional qualities like usability, availability, performance, etc.

This is primarily a functional requirement (user account registration). The phrase 'from any page in the system' indicates accessibility/convenience for users, implying a usability concern, but does not specify availability, performance, security, or other quality attributes.

Specifies how users authenticate (single password per user) which is a functional behavior of the login process and directly relates to security/authentication requirements, so labeled as Functional and Security.
Specifies use of SSL to secure payments and user logins, which is a security requirement (confidentiality/integrity/authentication). Does not specify functional behavior or other quality attributes.

Requirement explicitly states ease of maintenance so that another person can maintain with a manual and few hours training — this is a maintainability concern. No other quality attributes (performance, security, usability, etc.) are mentioned.

This requirement specifies a maximum time to complete an operation (placing an order), i.e. a performance/response-time constraint. It does not mention availability, security, usability, or other quality attributes explicitly, so only Performance is marked.

This requirement specifies a time-bound response for user registration (maximum 120 seconds), which is a performance constraint. It does not explicitly address availability, security, usability, or other quality aspects.

Requirement refers to the interface being "very user friendly", which targets usability (ease of use, intuitiveness). It does not explicitly mention look-and-feel, legal, performance, availability, or other quality attributes.

Explicitly requires a secure server to ensure confidentiality of customers' credit card and other details, which is a security requirement (confidentiality). No other quality attributes or functional behaviors are mentioned.

This requirement specifies a maximum page load time (response time) on a given connection, which is a performance constraint. Similar examples labeled such timing constraints as Performance and Availability; availability is included as it relates to service responsiveness/availability to users.

Requirement explicitly states ability to scale to 500 concurrent users by adding hardware, which directly concerns scalability. No explicit performance, availability, security, or other quality attributes are mentioned.
Specifies supporting 100 concurrent users without performance degradation — directly concerns performance (throughput/response) and system scalability to handle concurrent load.

Requirement describes deliberate throttling/graceful degradation under heavy load to preserve service for all users — this targets availability and fault tolerance. It does not explicitly state scalability, performance metrics, security, usability, or other concerns.

Requirement explicitly states portability across operating environments, which maps directly to Portability (PO). It does not mention availability, operability, performance, security, or other qualities.

MTBF is a reliability metric specifying minimum mean time between failures, which directly relates to system availability/reliability and fault tolerance. It does not describe functionality, performance, security, or other listed qualities.

Specifies capacity for simultaneous users and mirror servers (scalability). Calls for optimal performance and load balancing (performance). Mentions mirror servers and no user delay implying redundancy/resilience (fault tolerance) and continuous service (availability). No functional behavior, security, or other qualities explicitly required.

Requirement focuses on securing transactions, sensitive data storage and preventing unauthorized disclosure (security). It also references processing based on user agreement and avoiding unauthorized third-party transmission, implying legal/privacy/compliance concerns.

Specifies functional behavior (session timeout behavior and access to all E-store options) -> Functional. Session duration requirement relates to security (session management) and affects usability (user experience of staying logged in), so SE and US set to true. Other NFR categories not implied.

Text specifies user-friendly, navigable site, site map, easy finding of content (usability). Also mandates branding schemes and uniform layout (look & feel). No availability, security, performance, etc. requirements are stated.

Specifies the system must retrieve and display a case within 20 seconds (a performance/time constraint) and states 'regardless of ... number of cases' implying scalability. It also describes the functional behavior of retrieving/displaying a case.

Requirement addresses formatting and presentation to preserve readability when many links are present — concerns visual layout/appearance (Look & Feel) and user experience/accessibility (Usability). No functional, performance, security, or other non-functional aspects are specified.
Specifies visual presentation of links (dashed vs solid underline) — a look & feel requirement. Also impacts usability/readability by making link types distinguishable, so Usability applies.

Requirement concerns readability, visual presentation and refers to screen text legibility (ISO 9241-303). This addresses look-and-feel (visual/text layout) and usability (readability/accessibility). No functional, legal, performance, or other NFRs are implied.

Requirement specifies presentation and layout features (links, bullets, headings, short sentences) to support fast skimming—this is primarily about look-and-feel and usability (readability/navigation). No availability, performance, security, etc., are implied.

Requirement specifies how textual content should be presented (short sentences, chunks, bullet points) which directly concerns the user interface/look-and-feel and improves readability/usability. It does not specify functional behavior, performance, security, availability, etc.

Requirement concerns readability and quality of textual content (spelling/grammar) so it affects user comprehension and ease of use — a usability requirement. It does not specify legal, performance, availability, UI appearance, or other non-functional categories.

Requirement concerns user control over text size, which is an accessibility/usability concern (US) and pertains to presentation/look-and-feel of the UI (LF). It does not specify functional behavior or other non-functional categories.

The requirement prescribes designing UI input/output for diverse groups (formats for currency, units, dates, phone numbers, addresses) to be usable. This is a usability / UX requirement. It does not specify functional behavior, performance, security, portability, or other quality attributes explicitly, so only US is set.

Specifies what the system should display (clear explanatory error messages and suggested user actions) — a functional requirement — and addresses user-facing clarity and language matching the UI, which are usability concerns. No indication of availability, security, performance, scalability, portability, or maintainability.

Requirement targets reducing user errors (usability) and lowering effort to recover from errors (fault tolerance/error recovery). It does not specify availability, performance, security, portability, etc.

Requirement specifies acceptable page opening and download times across expected technical contexts (bandwidth) — a performance concern. It also emphasizes frequently accessed and navigation pages impacting user experience, so usability applies. No explicit availability, scalability, security, legal, or look-and-feel requirements.

Specifies system behavior (retrieve and display cases) so functional. Includes explicit timing requirement (5-8 seconds) -> performance. States requirement must hold regardless of number of cases/storage capacity, which implies a scalability constraint.

The requirement focuses on designing user interfaces to remain compatible with changing technologies and to present content across older and future user agents—this is primarily about portability/compatibility across platforms (PO). It also speaks to the interface being usable with future technologies, which pertains to usability (US). Other categories (security, performance, availability, etc.) are not implied.
Requirement concerns page layout and navigation to minimize scrolling and improve presentation and user experience; this is primarily Look & Feel and Usability.

The requirement specifies user interface behavior to avoid opening unnecessary/pop-up windows because they distract or hide information. This is primarily about UI presentation and user experience (Look & Feel and Usability). It does not specify availability, security, performance, portability, maintainability, operability, scalability, or functional system behavior beyond the UI guideline.
Requirement concerns UI behavior and presentation (avoid splash screens; provide skip option), which pertains to Look & Feel and overall Usability rather than functionality or security.

Requirement specifies minimizing navigation effort and accounting for user mental models and navigation strategies, which directly concerns usability (ease of use, navigation, learnability). It does not state functional behavior, availability, security, performance, or other NFRs explicitly.

The requirement specifies offering alternative navigation paths (a functionality to provide different ways to reach content) and is primarily about supporting different navigation strategies, which is a usability concern. It does not mention performance, security, legal, maintainability, etc.

Requirement specifies UI presentation of navigation context (where the user is), which is a look-and-feel requirement. It also explicitly demands clarity/sufficiency for users, which impacts usability.

Requirement specifies that navigation must help users understand location and paths (learnability, understandability) which is a usability concern. It does not impose availability, performance, portability, security, or maintenance constraints, nor purely visual styling.

This requirement mandates providing textual equivalents for non-text media to support accessibility and ease of use; it is an accessibility/usability quality requirement rather than a functional feature or other NFR category.

Requiring compliance with ISO 9241 is a standards/legal compliance requirement (L) and directly concerns user interface design/look-and-feel (LF). ISO 9241 also addresses usability and human–system interaction, so US is applicable. No other quality attributes are implied.
Requirement explicitly states UI should be user intuitive, which directly addresses usability. No mention of functionality, performance, security, etc.

Requirement explicitly demands the system be scalable and usable in small or large police stations with varying case volumes, which is a direct scalability concern. No other quality attributes (performance, portability, security, etc.) are mentioned.

This requirement concerns using familiar terminology for navigation links to improve user comprehension and ease of use, which is a usability concern rather than a functional, security, or performance requirement.

Requirement specifies UI design to support multiple input devices (keyboard operability) for ease of operation and accessibility. This is primarily a usability concern and affects operability/interaction; it does not impose legal, security, performance, or other qualities.

Requirement specifies how link labels should be worded to make content easy to understand and support users' tasks — this is a usability requirement. It also concerns the user interface wording/presentation, so Look & Feel applies. No indications of availability, security, performance, portability, scalability, maintainability, operability, or functional behavior.

This requirement concerns the user interface presentation and how navigation links should be visually distinguishable from action controls — it specifies look-and-feel aspects and directly impacts usability (clarity, user understanding). It does not specify functional behavior, performance, security, or other categories.

This requirement specifies time bounds for search operations (performance). The clause 'regardless of the storage capacity or number of cases' indicates a scalability constraint. It does not describe functional search features beyond returning a result list, nor other quality concerns.

Requirement specifies restore time after software or hardware failures (recovery within a fixed number of hours) which directly concerns fault tolerance and system availability/reliability. It does not specify functional behavior, security, performance, or other qualities.

This requirement limits allowed unplanned downtime incidents per period, which is a direct availability/reliability constraint. It does not specify functional behavior, fault-tolerance mechanisms, performance, security, or other qualities explicitly.
Specifies maximum allowed unplanned downtime over a rolling period, which is an availability/reliability requirement.
Defines when the system is considered 'down' (availability definition/criterion). Does not specify fault tolerance, operability, or other qualities.
Specifies a limit on planned downtime over a rolling three-month period, which is an availability requirement.
Specifies required availability windows (times/days). This is an availability requirement; no functional behavior or other quality attributes are mentioned.

Requirement mandates that user interfaces follow usability.gov guidelines, which concerns interface appearance and usability. This aligns with Look & Feel and Usability qualities; it does not specify legal compliance, performance, security, or other categories.
Specifies functional capabilities (view, modify, delete user-specified profiles on demand). No explicit non-functional constraints such as availability, security, usability, etc., are mentioned.

The requirement concerns informing users and making the currently used profile evident, which is about usability, transparency and user-facing information. It does not specify availability, performance, security, portability, maintainability, operability, scalability, fault tolerance, legal, or detailed functional behavior beyond user information, so only Usability is marked.

Requirement specifies that the system must make it evident to users when personalization/adaptation is active — this is about transparency and user experience (usability). It implies a UI indication but does not mandate legal, security, performance, or other quality attributes.

The requirement specifies the system should provide different access paths/navigation for user groups (a functional behavior) and emphasizes tailoring to tasks and information needs, which is a usability concern. No mention of availability, security, performance, etc.

The requirement specifies functionality to adapt/customize UI content and navigation for individual users/groups (a feature), and it explicitly aims to improve accessibility and ease of access (usability). It does not specify availability, performance, security, portability, scalability, legal, look-and-feel aesthetics, or maintenance/operability concerns.

This requirement specifies consistent placement of navigation components, which is a look-and-feel / user interface design constraint (LF) and directly affects usability (US). It does not specify functionality, performance, security, or other quality attributes.

Requirement specifies visual consistency and highlighting in the navigation component and how the UI should present state to the user—this pertains to look-and-feel and usability (navigation clarity), not functional behavior or other non-functional categories.

This requirement specifies a feature: provide a separate navigation overview/site map (functional). It also targets usability by helping users understand site structure and navigate the application (usability). No explicit non-functional aspects like performance, security, availability, etc., are mentioned.

Requirement specifies user-interface/navigation design (each page must include a link to home/landmark). This is about look-and-feel and ease of navigation (usability). It does not specify functional behavior, performance, security, availability, etc.

The requirement prescribes design principles for presentation, interaction, and multimedia (visual/layout concerns) and cites ISO usability/accessibility standards. This clearly concerns Look & Feel and Usability. It does not specify availability, security, performance, portability, scalability, maintainability, operability, or legal constraints explicitly.

Specifies consistent placement of page titles across pages, which concerns the user interface appearance (Look & Feel) and improves usability by providing predictable navigation; it does not address other quality attributes.

This requirement specifies consistent page layout and grouping of pages to help users find information—it is a look-and-feel/UI design requirement (LF) and directly relates to usability (US). It does not specify availability, performance, security, portability, scalability, maintainability, operability, fault tolerance, or functional behavior.

Requirement specifies providing alternative text-only presentation when frames or style sheets are unavailable, addressing accessibility and ease of use—an usability (accessibility) concern rather than performance, security, or functional behavior.

Requirement addresses use of color in UI—both visual appearance (look & feel) and accessibility/usability for users with color perception issues. Does not specify functionality or other quality attributes.

Specifies page length and presentation appropriate to purpose—this is a look-and-feel/layout requirement and affects usability/readability. No functional, performance, security, or other quality attributes are explicitly required.

Requirement concerns page visual layout and spacing affecting visual skimming and organization (Look & Feel) and directly addresses ease of scanning/readability for users (Usability). No mention of functionality, performance, security, etc.

Requires the system to provide a printer-friendly version (functional). Specifies output layout, paper format and orientation acceptable to the user, which concerns presentation/look-and-feel. Also improves usability for reading/printing, so usability is applicable. No explicit requirements about availability, performance, security, portability, maintainability, scalability, fault tolerance, or legal constraints.

This is a user interface requirement specifying how links should appear (visual marking) and affects usability (helping users understand behavior), so Look & Feel and Usability apply. It does not specify functionality, performance, security, etc.

This requirement specifies response time expectations (performance) for common functions under standard and peak load—explicitly a performance concern. Mention of peak conditions implies scalability (ability to handle increased load). No indication of other qualities.

Specifies adherence to accessibility standards for UI/content (usability/accessibility) and a UI requirement that the application logo links to home — these are look-and-feel and usability concerns rather than security, performance, portability, etc.

Specifies UI interaction design to minimize clicks—this is primarily a usability requirement (efficiency of user tasks). It also implies UI/layout considerations, so Look & Feel is marked. No functional behavior, security, performance, etc., are specified.

Specifies that the help feature must be accessible (functional requirement) and available in both offline and online modes, implying resilience to loss of connectivity (fault tolerance). Does not mention security, performance, scalability, etc.

This requirement specifies a feature to provide context-sensitive help across all UIs (functional) and targets user assistance/usability (improves learnability and ease of use). It does not mention availability, performance, security, portability, etc.

The requirement explicitly focuses on scalability and performance techniques (caching, async sockets, batching, paging, minimizing fetched fields) — so mark Performance and Scalability. It also specifies AJAX and UX-related behaviors to improve user experience, so Usability is applicable. No explicit availability, security, portability, maintainability, legal, fault-tolerance, operability or functional requirements are stated.

The requirement explicitly describes security and access control controls: preventing XSS and SQL injection, input validation/sanitization/encoding, parameterized queries, client/server validation, and use of soft deletes for data protection. These are security-related measures; no other quality attributes (availability, performance, usability, etc.) are mentioned.
Requirement explicitly mandates secure transmission mechanisms (SSL, two-way digital signatures), which concerns confidentiality/integrity/authentication — a security non-functional requirement.

Specifies a capability (support selective encryption) which is a functional requirement and directly concerns data protection via encryption, a security requirement. No indication of availability, performance, etc.
Requirement specifies cross-browser support/compatibility, which is a portability concern. It does not state functional behavior or other quality attributes.
Specifies use of HTTPS/SSL which is a security requirement for encrypted communications (confidentiality and integrity). No other quality attributes are mentioned.

Requirement specifies that the system should support virtual private network connections (functional capability) and emphasizes they be secure, implying security concerns (confidentiality/integrity). No explicit statements about availability, fault-tolerance, scalability, portability, legal compliance, usability, or other qualities.

Specifies support for SSL encrypted connections, which is a security requirement (confidentiality/integrity of communications). No other quality attributes (availability, performance, etc.) are mentioned.
Specifies capability to support public access (a functional requirement). Implies access control decisions about which data/functionality are public, so security is relevant.

This requirement specifies a capability the system must provide (support multiple communication service types for remote access), which is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly state platform compatibility, availability, security, or other quality attributes.

This specifies a functional requirement to provide an interface for logging and tracking defects/enhancements. No explicit non-functional qualities (security, availability, usability, etc.) are stated.

Specifying browser-based access and minimal client requirements indicates platform independence/compatibility across client devices (Portability). It also implies ease of use/accessibility from typical client devices (Usability). It does not explicitly state availability, security, performance, or other concerns.

The requirement specifies extensibility to support access via PDAs and mobile data terminals. This implies portability across device platforms (PO) and an extensible/maintainable architecture (MN). It does not explicitly address availability, security, performance, usability, scalability, legal, look-and-feel, or operability.

Specifies architectural separation of concerns (presentation/business/data-access), which primarily targets maintainability/modifiability. Other quality attributes (scalability, portability, operability) are not explicitly stated.

Specifies deployment architecture (3-tier datacenter), which relates to operability/administration and deployment requirements. It does not state functional behavior, performance, scalability, security, portability, or usability explicitly.

Specifies deployment and maintenance approach (centralized deployment and maintenance). This directly concerns maintainability (how maintenance is organized) and operability/administration (deployment/operation model). Does not specify functional behavior or other quality attributes.

The requirement mandates using a common User Access and Authentication Service to provide Single Sign-On, which is primarily a security/authentication requirement. It does not specify functional behavior, availability, usability, or other quality attributes explicitly.

Specifying development on Open Standards is a constraint about technologies and interoperability/compatibility. This implies portability/compatibility across platforms (PO) and is similar to other technology-stack constraints labeled as Operability (O) because it affects integration, deployment, and maintainability/operation.

Specifies an architectural style (SOA) and modular design—these are design/architecture constraints that primarily target maintainability (modularity, separation of concerns). It does not explicitly state availability, fault-tolerance, performance, portability, scalability, security, operability, usability, or legal requirements.

The requirement explicitly specifies performance under low-bandwidth conditions (satisfactory performance in police stations connected on low-bandwidth), which is a performance quality attribute. It does not mention availability, fault tolerance, usability, portability, or other categories.

Requirement specifies the system must operate in offline mode providing critical functionality — this is both a functional behavior (operate offline for key features) and a fault-tolerance/resilience concern (continue operating despite loss of connectivity). No explicit availability, performance, security, usability, or other quality attributes are mentioned.

Requirement specifies that operational data must not be lost during equipment or network failures — this is a fault-tolerance requirement. It also implies availability/reliability of the system during such failures, so Availability is applicable. No indication of security, performance, usability, etc.

Specifies a system capability (support multilingual interface) — a functional feature — and relates to the user interface/experience (look & feel and usability). No explicit availability, performance, security, portability, etc. requirements.

This requirement specifies that the system must provide a GUI customization feature (functional behavior) and enumerates aspects that affect appearance (menu contents, layout, colours, fonts), so Look & Feel is applicable. Allowing user customization also targets usability/accessibility, so Usability is marked. No explicit requirements about availability, fault tolerance, security, portability, scalability, maintainability, or legal constraints are stated.

Specifying standardized formats and common metadata primarily targets interoperability/compatibility across platforms and data exchange, which maps to Portability. It does not explicitly state availability, security, UI, or maintenance requirements.

This requirement specifies a system behavior: sending alerts/notifications (email, SMS) when actions occur and allowing the user to opt in. This is a functional requirement about notification functionality. It does not explicitly state availability, performance, security, portability, or usability constraints.
Specifies support for multi-tier authentication, which is a security requirement (authentication mechanisms). It does not state availability, performance, portability, or other qualities.

This requirement specifies a user capability to view reports filtered by category, status, and age — a functional behavior. It does not state availability, performance, security, UI appearance, or other quality constraints.

This requirement specifies a system feature (persistent, user-definable and context-derived data-entry defaults) — a functional requirement. It also clearly targets usability by reducing user effort and improving data-entry efficiency, so Usability is applicable. No explicit availability, performance, security, scalability, portability, maintainability, legal, look-and-feel, or fault-tolerance constraints are stated.

This requirement specifies a user-facing capability—tracking submitted defect/enhancement requests—which is a functional behavior. It does not mention availability, performance, security, usability, or other quality attributes.

The requirement mandates customizable/user-configurable interfaces and persistence of those configurations in the user profile, which specifies system behavior (functional) and affects the UI appearance (look & feel) and user interaction (usability). No explicit availability, security, performance, portability, scalability, maintainability, operability, or legal concerns are mentioned.

This specifies a system capability — the ability to display multiple entities at once — which is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly state availability, performance, UI aesthetics, usability, or other non-functional constraints.
Specifies user interface rules to provide a familiar/common look and feel (Look & Feel). This also implies improved usability (familiarity), so US is set.

Requirement concerns the content and presentation of error messages and guidance for user action—a usability concern. It also implies presentation/wording aspects, so Look & Feel applies. No performance, security, availability, etc., are specified.

The requirement mandates that all access and activities be recorded in an audit trail (functional behavior). It explicitly cites legal admissibility (Legal) and aiding data recovery (Fault Tolerance). Recording access for accountability implies security (audit/logging) concerns. Other non-functional categories (performance, scalability, usability, portability, look-and-feel, maintainability, operability, availability) are not explicitly mentioned.

This requirement mandates logging of unauthorised access attempts (audit trail), which is a security control (detection/auditing). It does not specify availability, performance, UI, portability, maintainability, scalability, or other qualities.
This requirement specifies access-control behavior for search results (security). It also prescribes system behavior (functional). No other quality attributes are explicitly mentioned.

This requirement specifies how the system must respond (functional behavior) and explicitly concerns whether case information is revealed or hidden, which is a confidentiality/security constraint. No explicit availability, performance, portability, scalability, maintainability, legal, usability, or fault-tolerance aspects are mentioned.

This requirement specifies access control for modifying security attributes, which is a security (SE) requirement. It does not primarily address availability, performance, UI, portability, scalability, maintainability, operability, fault tolerance, legal, or usability concerns, so those labels are not set.

This specifies a system capability (allow a user to stipulate access) — a functional requirement — and describes access control permissions, which is a security concern. No other quality attributes (availability, scalability, etc.) are implied.

This requirement specifies system behavior (allowing setup of user profiles and group allocation) which is functional. It also explicitly restricts the capability to admin-users only, which is an access control/authorization constraint, so it concerns security. No indications of availability, performance, scalability, portability, legal, UI look-and-feel, maintainability, or operability requirements.

The requirement mandates the system provide End User and Administrator functions (a functional statement) and emphasizes suitability for users with special needs and compatibility with specialist software and interface guidelines—this clearly targets usability (US) and look-and-feel (LF). Referencing compliance with specific interface guidelines implies a contractual/standards constraint, so Legal (L) is set. No explicit statements about availability, security, performance, scalability, portability, maintainability, or operability were made.
Specifies role-based control of functionality (access/permissions), which is an access control/security requirement rather than functional behavior or other quality attributes.
This requirement specifies a functional capability (users can belong to multiple groups). It does not mention availability, performance, security, usability, or other quality attributes.

Specifies access from internal application and externally via browser (availability/accessibility). External access implies security concerns (authorization/authentication), similar to provided example.

Specifies a system behavior: when audit trail is activated, the system must automatically track events and store information. This is a functional requirement; it does not explicitly state availability, security, or other quality attributes.

Requires the system to maintain an audit trail (functional) and specifies retention duration tied to case life, implying compliance/record-keeping obligation (legal). No explicit performance, availability, security, or other quality constraints mentioned.

Requirement specifies a system function to make audit trail data available for inspection (Functional). It restricts access to 'authorised external personnel', implying authorization/security concerns (Security). The need for access by personnel with little or no familiarity implies usability/learnability considerations for the interface (Usability). No explicit availability, fault tolerance, performance, portability, scalability, legal, maintainability, look-and-feel, or operability requirements are stated.

This requirement specifies a concrete system capability (export audit trails) so it's functional. The clause 'without affecting the audit trail stored by the System' implies preservation/integrity of audit data, which is a security-related concern, so Security is marked. No explicit availability, performance, scalability, portability, maintainability, legal, look-and-feel, operability, or usability constraints are stated.

Requirement specifies the system must record an audit trail of actions (functional behavior). Audit trails are a security/control feature for accountability, so Security is also applicable. No explicit availability, performance, portability, etc., are mentioned.

Requirement specifies that the system must capture and store access-control violations and attempted violations (a logging/auditing capability) — this is a security requirement and also describes a concrete system function (capture/store), so labeled SE and F.

The requirement specifies a system capability to provide reports organized by case, by user, and chronologically — this describes functional behavior (reporting feature). It does not mention availability, performance, security, UI look-and-feel, or other non-functional concerns.

This is a functional requirement specifying that the system must provide reports (functional). The reporting is for operational/administrative purposes (organized by workstation/network address), which supports operability (monitoring/auditing), but it does not explicitly state security, performance, availability, or other quality attributes.

This requirement specifies a system capability (allow users to limit access to cases) — a functional requirement — and describes access control/authorization which is a security concern, so mark F and SE. No explicit availability, fault-tolerance, usability, or other quality attributes are stated.
Specifies a functional capability (acquire shipping charges) plus a quantitative response-time constraint (<2 seconds), indicating both functional and performance requirements.

Requirement concerns consistent symbols/colors—a look-and-feel concern—and aims to improve clarity of notifications, which is a usability attribute. No functional, performance, security, or other quality aspects are specified.

This requirement specifies the time to deploy and make the system operational upon a USB plug-in, which concerns installability/operability (manageability/deployment). It does not specify functional behavior, performance of runtime operations, security, portability, or usability.

Specifies required capacity for concurrent users (ability to scale to 1000 simultaneous logged-in customers). This is a scalability requirement; no explicit availability, performance, security, or functional behavior beyond capacity is stated.

This requirement specifies a throughput/latency constraint (retrieve 200 products per second), which is a performance (PE) quality attribute. It does not describe functional behavior beyond the performance target nor other quality aspects.
Specifies a functional capability (add product to shopping cart) with a quantitative timing constraint (<2ms), which is a performance non-functional requirement.
Specifies the functional capability to search for a product and a quantitative time constraint (<1 second) which is a performance requirement. No other quality attributes are implied.

Specifies UI design requirement about button placement/visibility (look & feel) and directly impacts usability (ease of locating controls). No functional, performance, security, or other quality aspects are implied.
Specifies a functional capability (sending email to customer and vendor) with an explicit timing constraint (<1 second), which is a performance requirement.
Specifies a system capability (validate credit card) — functional — with a quantitative timing constraint (<2 seconds), which is a performance requirement.

Requirement specifies friendly, easy-to-read error messages—this relates to user interface appearance/readability (Look & Feel) and overall usability (ease of understanding). No indication of availability, security, performance, etc.
Specifies the ability to restore records (functional behavior) with a quantitative throughput requirement (performance). No indication of availability, scalability, security, etc.
Specifies use of a firewall (Firestarter) to protect the system — a clear security requirement regarding protection/defense.

The statement specifies a required system action ('shall encrypt...') so it is functional. It specifically mandates encryption over HTTPS, which is a security requirement (confidentiality/integrity), so SE is set.
