Specifies a concrete system behavior (opening a new window) in response to a user action, which is a functional requirement. It does not state availability, performance, security, portability, look-and-feel constraints, or other non-functional aspects.

Specifies GUI behavior: display of stdout/stderr in a tab-selectable window and clearing rules before execution — this is a functional requirement about UI behavior and also relates to look-and-feel/layout of the output window.

This requirement specifies concrete behavior of the HATS-GUI (how it should suggest file names in various copy scenarios), which is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly state availability, performance, security, scalability, portability, maintenance, operability, legal, or look-and-feel concerns. Although it aids usability, the statement defines specific functionality rather than a general usability quality, so US is not set.

Specifies a required artifact (a single file) and its format/extension — this is a functional/structural requirement about what the system/application must provide. It does not mention availability, performance, security, portability, or other quality attributes explicitly.

Specifies a functional constraint on the system artifact (there shall be exactly one grammar file with .grm extension). It defines what must exist rather than an NFR like performance, security, or usability.
This requirement specifies a system artifact and naming/quantity constraint (one file with .spec extension), which defines functional behavior/structure rather than a non-functional quality.

This requirement specifies a deployment/operational naming convention for application file directories, which impacts operability (deployment, administration) and also aids maintainability (consistency for developers/administrators). It does not specify functional behavior or other quality attributes.

Specifies a concrete system behavior (keyboard cursor movement via arrow keys), i.e., a functional requirement. It does not explicitly address availability, performance, usability, security, or other non-functional aspects.

Specifies a user-facing capability (creating and naming an application composed of specific files) — a functional requirement. No explicit non-functional constraints (availability, performance, security, etc.) are stated.

Specifies where application files must be stored (a storage/behavioral requirement) — primarily a functional constraint about data organization. Does not explicitly state maintainability, operability, security, or other quality attributes.

Requirement specifies a menu item providing an interface and behavior (selecting SDTs and style files, formatting) — this is functional. It also mandates presentation/formatting according to styles, which relates to look-and-feel, so LF is set. No explicit availability, security, performance, portability, scalability, maintainability, operability, or legal constraints are mentioned.

Specifies a menu item that provides an interface for viewing, navigating, and searching SDT outputs — this describes functional behavior (what the system should do). No quality attributes (usability, security, performance, etc.) are explicitly stated.

Specifies a system capability (providing an interface for viewing and searching pretty-printed text), which is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly state usability, performance, security, or other non-functional qualities.

Requirement specifies a functional capability: a menu item that provides an interface to view error strings (Functional). It also describes a user-facing interface/menu item, implying usability concerns (Usability). No explicit statements about security, availability, performance, scalability, portability, fault tolerance, maintainability, operability, or legal/visual styling details, so those are not marked.

Specifies a system capability: a menu item that provides an interface to select and execute transformation programs — a functional requirement. No explicit quality attributes (performance, security, usability, etc.) are stated.

This statement specifies a system capability: a menu item that provides an interface for selecting text associated with SDT displays, which is a functional requirement. It does not specify availability, security, performance, UI aesthetics, or other quality attributes.

This specifies a functional behavior: a menu item shall provide an interface to copy selected text into the OS clipboard. It does not state availability, security, performance, usability, or other non-functional concerns.

Specifies functional requirements for the HATS-GUI to interface with HATS-SML (parse, execute, create outputs, pass args, capture stdout/stderr) — clearly functional. Mentions HATS-SML version 2.0 and command-line compatibility, implying a portability/compatibility constraint. No explicit availability, performance, security, usability, etc.

The requirement specifies GUI functionality to create/modify/copy/delete applications or files — a clear functional behavior. It does not explicitly state non-functional concerns such as availability, fault tolerance, usability, security, or others, so only the Functional label is set.

The requirement specifies concrete system behavior (display a specific error message and include OS-provided failure details), which is functional. It also prescribes informative error reporting to the user, which impacts usability (clear feedback), so US is set. It does not mandate availability, recovery, security, performance, portability, scalability, legal, look-and-feel, maintainability, or operability concerns explicitly.

Specifies a system function: a menu item that provides an interface to view debugging information (functional). Also references a UI element (menu item/interface), so Look & Feel applies. No mention of security, performance, availability, etc.

Requirement specifies behaviour of processing functions (must be chainable and repeatable) — this is a functional requirement. It also implies a design-for-maintainability/reusability constraint (modular, composable processing), so Maintainability is marked. It does not explicitly address availability, performance, scalability, security, portability, fault tolerance, operability, legal, look & feel, or usability.

Requirement specifies behavior (flagging corrupted data and proceeding) — functional. It explicitly requires graceful handling so processing of other data is unaffected and no interruption — this is fault tolerance. Ensuring continuation without interruption implies availability/reliability concerns, so Availability is also applicable. No explicit security, performance, scalability, portability, legal, UI, maintainability, or operability constraints are stated.

Requirement mandates minimizing overhead by leveraging language, compiler, and system features—this is a performance/efficiency constraint; no explicit availability, security, portability, scalability, or other concerns are stated.

The requirement explicitly mandates optimizing use of language, compiler, and system features to minimize run times, which is a performance-oriented quality attribute. It does not mention availability, fault tolerance, security, portability, scalability, usability, or maintainability.

Requirement specifies non-functional capacity and speed characteristics: 'sufficient storage... access speeds' maps to Performance. It requires standby reserve to meet reliability and outage recovery and meet demands, which implies Availability and Fault Tolerance. It does not address legal, UI, security, portability, maintainability, operability, or usability explicitly.

Requirement specifies memory capacity and access speeds to prevent loss or delay of data streams — this is a performance/resource constraint (throughput/latency). It does not explicitly address availability, fault tolerance, security, scalability, or other qualities.

Requirement specifies CPU capacity to prevent processing delays and data loss on input/output streams — this is a performance requirement (throughput/latency) and implies scalability/capacity to handle load. It does not address availability, fault tolerance, security, or other categories explicitly.

Specifies numeric throughput requirement (25 MBytes/sec) => Performance. States this includes resends and transfer after an e2e connection outage => implies fault-tolerance/recovery handling. Notes that this is initial and will be increased over time => scalability. No functional behavior, security, availability, portability, etc., are explicitly required.

Specifies required data throughput (1.6 GBytes/sec) and simultaneous input/output—this is a performance (throughput/latency) constraint and notes future increases, implying scalability. No security, availability, or usability aspects are mentioned.

Requirement concerns minimizing overhead and latency of I/O and storage operations by using system resources efficiently, which is a performance-quality constraint. It does not specify functionality, availability, security, scalability, or other categories.

The requirement specifies that the system shall continue operations (possibly degraded) on unaffected resources during partial shutdowns for maintenance/repair/upgrade. This directly concerns availability and graceful degradation/resilience (fault tolerance). It does not specify legal, performance, security, portability, scalability, usability, or maintainability metrics, nor an explicit operability/admin feature.

The requirement prescribes coding practices, documentation, choice of familiar languages, and readable style to reduce confusion—these directly target maintainability (ease of modification, understanding, and onboarding). It does not specify runtime performance, availability, security, UI look-and-feel, portability, scalability, or functional behavior.

Requirement specifies that hardware specifications and configuration information be readily available — this supports operability (administration, configuration, deployment) and maintainability (ease of maintenance, understanding system configuration). It does not address availability, performance, security, portability, scalability, or UI aspects.

Requirement mandates modular design and hot‑swappable components, which directly target replaceability/maintainability (MN). Hot‑swappability also implies improved availability (A) and supports fault tolerance/ graceful recovery (FT). It also impacts operability/administration (O) by enabling easier component replacement without downtime.

Requirement specifies a capability (Test Mode) to handle non-real-time operations 'as if real-time' — this implies both a functional capability (ability to process non-real-time inputs) and a performance/timing quality constraint (treating them with real-time behavior). No explicit mentions of availability, scalability, security, etc.

This requirement specifies what the backend (BE) must do: deliver formatted final results and all data for archiving/processing (functional). It also mandates compatibility with a specific data format (AIPS++ Measurement Sets), which implies interoperability/portability requirements, so Portability is set. No explicit availability, performance, security, legal, UI, scalability, maintainability, operability, or usability constraints are stated.

This requirement specifies a functional capability (providing selectable debug/test message levels). It explicitly supports operability (monitoring/diagnostics) and also contributes to maintainability (facilitates debugging and testing). No indications of availability, performance, security, portability, scalability, legal, look-and-feel, or usability requirements.

Specifies a functional capability (provide error/warning reports). Implies fault-handling/diagnostics (FT) and supports maintainability (helps troubleshooting). Reporting to M&C is an operability/monitoring requirement (O). No explicit availability, security, performance, portability, scalability, or UI concerns.

Requirement specifies functional behavior: providing operational status data and receiving control data (data exchange with M&C). It also implies operability/management aspects (monitoring and control integration), but does not mention availability, security, performance, or UI/look-and-feel.

This statement specifies required system behavior (the BE shall receive metadata via M&C to format results for delivery), which is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly state availability, fault tolerance, security, performance, operability or other non-functional concerns.

Spec mandates use of industry-standard, widely available OS/middleware/languages which impacts operability (manageability/administration), maintainability (common tech and source availability ease maintenance), and portability/compatibility (widely used platforms). No explicit performance, security, legal, or UI requirements stated.

This requirement specifies a functional behavior: the back-end (BE) shall receive specific data/parameters via M&C for processing correlator lag values. It describes what the system must do; it does not impose availability, fault-tolerance, security, performance, or other non-functional constraints.

The requirement specifies that the backend must maintain data fidelity and dynamic range across processing and I/O — this is a functional obligation (what the system shall do) and a data integrity/security concern (ensuring data is not corrupted). It does not explicitly address availability, fault tolerance, performance, portability, scalability, maintainability, operability, UI, usability, or legal constraints.

The requirement specifies a self-monitoring, self-correcting capability (functional behavior) focused on detecting/reporting and automatically remedying failures—this is primarily Fault Tolerance. It also implies operability (monitoring/reporting/manageability) and maintainability (self-diagnosis aids maintenance). Because the goal is to lessen impact of failures and communications disruptions it implicitly targets availability. No explicit statements about security, performance metrics, portability, scalability, legal, look-and-feel, or usability.

Requirement specifies hardware must be easily expandable, reconfigurable, augmentable and replaceable to handle increasing data/processing demands. This primarily concerns scalability (ability to grow) and implies maintainability (replaceable, reconfigurable) and operability/administrability. It does not explicitly state availability, fault tolerance, security, portability, or performance metrics.

Specifies continuous operation/no complete loss of service (availability) and mentions resilience except in total power failure (fault tolerance/redundancy). No functional behavior or other quality attributes implied.
Specifies a functional behavior: the backend (BE) shall receive State Count data via M&C from the Correlator. No quality attributes (availability, performance, security, etc.) are implied.

This specifies an administrative capability (functional). It also describes access control and session termination behavior (security). It pertains to system administration/management functions (operability). No explicit availability, performance, portability, etc., requirements are stated.

This specifies a capability (administrator can edit a user's system access properties), which is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly state security constraints, operability, performance, availability, or other quality attributes.
This is a functional requirement specifying an administrative capability (remove a user). It does not state availability, security, performance, or other non-functional concerns.
This requirement specifies a functional capability (administrator can create/add a user). It does not mention availability, performance, security, UI, or other quality attributes.

Requirement specifies per-user access properties/privileges (which subsystems/tools a user may access) — this is an access control requirement, i.e., a security concern. It does not state availability, performance, UI, portability, or maintainability constraints.

Specifies unrestricted access for a system administrator (access control/authorization) which is a security requirement (SE) and also pertains to system operation/administration privileges (O). No other quality attributes are implied.
Requirement specifies security of login attempts (e.g., encrypted passwords), which is a security concern (confidentiality/integrity). No other quality attributes or functional behaviors are implied.

This requirement specifies that users must authenticate using unique identification (username/password), which is an authentication/security constraint. It does not explicitly state other quality attributes (availability, performance, usability) or broader functional behavior beyond authentication.
Specifies throughput requirement (2 Gbytes/sec per channel in real-time) and explicitly mentions scalability; this indicates both performance (throughput/real-time) and scalability concerns.

Requirement specifies the software must continue operating without a total restart after internal failures between maintenance windows, which describes fault tolerance/resilience (FT) and implies availability (A). It does not state functional behavior, maintainability, performance, security, etc.

Requirement demands that changes be seamless at interfaces and not affect hardware/software modules—this concerns integration/compatibility and the system's operability/interaction with other components (operability) and cross-module/platform compatibility (portability). No explicit performance, security, availability, or maintainability demands.

The requirement specifies that OS software must provide source code or sufficient diagnostics and customer support. This addresses maintainability (ability to diagnose, fix, and modify) and operability (diagnostics and support for operating/administering the system). It does not explicitly require legal/licensing, portability, performance, security, availability, scalability, usability, or functional behavior.

Requirement mandates delivery of a complete diagnostic package and customer support for closed-source tools, which primarily supports maintainability (easier maintenance, troubleshooting) and operability (administration, supportability). It does not specify functional behavior, security, performance, availability, portability, scalability, legal, look-and-feel, or usability aspects.

The requirement specifies management properties of processes (killable, restartable, debuggable, testable) which directly concern operability (O) and maintainability (MN). Being able to restart/kill without affecting normal operations and thus not impacting service implies availability/resilience (A) and also relates to fault tolerance (FT). No security, performance, portability, scalability, legal, look-and-feel or usability aspects are mentioned.

Requirement specifies that modules must be debuggable, which directly relates to maintainability (ease of diagnosing and fixing software). It does not specify operational/admin features, security, performance, or other non-functional categories.

Requires source code be available on systems that execute it, which supports maintainability (access to code for modification/bugfix) and operability/deployability (code must be present/manageable on execution systems). It also implies portability/deployability across execution environments (PO). Does not explicitly address availability, security, performance, scalability, legal, or UI.

Specifies that hardware must be readily accessible for maintenance, repair, replacement, or reconfiguration — this directly addresses maintainability and operability (administration/maintenance activities). No functional behavior, performance, security, portability, scalability, legal, or UI concerns are implied.

Requirement specifies a functional capability (standby/resume) and a quality constraint on resume delay (performance/latency). No explicit availability, fault-tolerance, security, usability, or other NFRs are mentioned.

Requirement defines required behavior during loss of the M&C system (functional behavior) and specifies that the system must continue to operate despite the loss (an availability requirement). It also describes graceful degradation and use of cached data to complete operations in the face of missing auxiliary data, which is fault-tolerance/resilience. No explicit mentions of performance, security, scalability, portability, usability, legal, maintainability, look-and-feel, or operability were given.

The requirement specifies system behavior ('shall be able to complete processing...deliver the results') which makes it functional. It describes behavior under a failure scenario (Loss of Correlator) and the need to continue processing and resume operations, which directly implies fault tolerance. It also explicitly states maintaining availability for immediate resumption, so Availability is applicable. No mention of security, performance metrics, portability, maintainability, UI, scalability, operability, or legal concerns.

Requirement specifies continued operation despite temporary loss of availability of the e2e system — this is explicitly about availability and graceful handling of failures (fault tolerance). No functional behavior beyond that, and no indications of security, performance, scalability, etc.

Requirement specifies that functionality in 3.7.1 must be accomplished in a way that is transparent to processing, communications and I/O software (with possible exception of recompilation). This implies minimal impact on existing operational/admin interfaces and integration (operability) and that the feature should work without changes across software environments (portability). It does not state performance, security, availability, legal, UI, scalability, or explicit maintainability concerns, so those labels are not set.

This requirement constrains how data must be transferred to ensure all data required for a Fourier Transform resides on a single processor, which is a performance/data-locality constraint (affecting efficiency/processing latency). It does not specify legal, security, usability, availability, or maintainability aspects, nor broader functional behavior beyond the transfer quality.

Requirement specifies the system must respond to mode-related I/O and processing changes in a loss-less manner, i.e., tolerate faults/changes without data loss. This indicates fault tolerance/resilience rather than functional behavior or other NFR categories.

Specifies a capability to report the functional state of internal components (a functional requirement) and implies monitoring/operability concerns (status/reporting for administrators). It does not specify availability, security, performance, or other NFRs.

The requirement specifies concrete system behavior: summing spectral results, control via an observational-mode parameter, tracking number of samples integrated, and ordering relative to FFT—this is functional. It also imposes an output-rate constraint (integration to throttle correlator output to a rate manageable by the E2E), which is a performance/throughput requirement. No explicit availability, fault tolerance, security, usability, portability, scalability, maintainability, operability, legal, or look-and-feel aspects are stated.

The requirement specifies functional behavior: the backend shall apply user-selected frequency-domain processes and support chaining/repeatability of processing steps. It does not state availability, performance, security, portability, scalability, usability, or other non-functional constraints explicitly, so only Functional is set.

Specifies a required capability (perform FFT with specific algorithm and retention) — functional. Also requires accepting inputs from time-domain processes, implying an interface/operability requirement. No mention of performance, security, portability, etc.

Requirement specifies system capability: applying user-selected time-domain processes and chaining/repeatability of processing steps—this is a functional behavior. It does not state availability, performance, security, portability, scalability, maintainability, operability, legal, look-and-feel, or usability constraints, so no other labels are set.

This describes a required system capability (perform windowing operations before and after Fourier Transform for RFI mitigation and convolution), which is a functional requirement. It does not specify availability, performance metrics, security, or other non-functional aspects.

This requirement specifies a capability the backend (BE) must provide — the ability to perform time-stamp adjustments based on observational mode and correlator output (functional behavior). It does not mention availability, performance, security, usability, or other non-functional aspects.

Specifies a backend capability to apply a specific correction (VanVleck)—this is a functional requirement describing system behavior. No explicit non-functional constraints (performance, availability, security, etc.) are stated.

Describes a capability of the backend to apply data normalizations based on reported invalid data counts — this specifies functional behavior. No explicit non-functional qualities (availability, performance, security, etc.) are stated.

The requirement specifies a backend function: keeping track/counting invalid data items. This describes functional behavior (F). It does not explicitly state availability, security, performance, operability, or other quality attributes.

The requirement specifies a concrete system behavior ('shall ensure... compare... and report'), so it is Functional. It concerns data integrity (valid values, correct ordering), which maps to Security (integrity). The requirement also mandates reporting out-of-tolerance conditions, implying monitoring/operational alerting, so Operability is applicable. It does not mention availability, fault recovery, maintainability, performance, portability, scalability, UI, usability or legal constraints.
Describes a functional behavior: combining spectra with metadata into formatted output (AIPS++ Measurement Sets). No explicit non-functional qualities (performance, security, etc.) are stated.

The statement specifies a functional behavior: the back-end shall assemble input data into continuous time series (lag sets). It does not mention availability, performance, security, scalability, or other quality attributes.

Requirement specifies concrete system behavior (store input records, track buffer locations) -> Functional. It requires detection/reporting of buffer overflows and tracking for correct processing, which addresses error handling and resilience -> Fault Tolerance. The explicit demand to report overflow conditions supports operational monitoring/administration -> Operability.

This is primarily a functional requirement (the BE shall verify receipt). It explicitly requires error checking, accumulation of error statistics and reporting out-of-tolerance conditions, which implies fault detection/handling concerns (FT). The requirement also concerns operational monitoring and reporting useful for operators/admins, so Operability is applicable. It does not mention availability targets, security, maintainability, performance, scalability, portability, legal, or UI/look-and-feel.

This statement specifies a functional behavior (the backend shall receive incoming data packets over a named network interface). It does not state availability, performance, security, or other quality constraints.
Specifies maximum capacity (size of lag sets the backend must handle), which is a scalability/capacity requirement rather than functional, performance, or other categories.

Specifies capacity constraint on handling 'lag frames' size (<128 values), which is a performance and scalability requirement about workload/throughput. No legal, security, availability, or UI aspects implied.

"Guarantee safe delivery of all internal messages" implies reliability/resilience (fault tolerance/reliable delivery) and security (safety of messages — confidentiality/integrity). It does not explicitly state availability, performance, portability, or other categories.

Requirement specifies backend behavior: verify successful delivery of output to end-to-end system — primary is a functional requirement. It also implies an operational/monitoring concern (verifying delivery), so Operability is marked. No explicit availability, fault tolerance, security, performance, or other qualities stated.

The requirement specifies a system behavior: the BE shall notify M&C when interruptions are detected. This is a functional notification requirement; it does not explicitly state availability, fault-tolerance, operability, security, or other non-functional attributes.

This requirement specifies a functional behavior: the backend (BE) must acknowledge receipt of all data from the Monitor & Control system. It defines what the system should do rather than an availability, performance, security, or other quality attribute.

Specifies a functional behavior: the backend (BE) shall receive specific lag frame formats from the Correlator, including transport via UDP/IP. This describes what the system must do rather than an NFR.

The statement specifies required system behavior: respond to mode changes and parameter updates and synchronize the processing pipeline (functional). It also describes operational/manageability actions (updating internal tables, synchronizing pipeline) related to operating/administering the system, so Operability is applicable. It does not explicitly address availability, performance, security, scalability, portability, legality, UI, or maintainability.

Requires the system to store and manage output data and report errors (functional). Specifies backup disk buffering and retention until successful transfer (fault tolerance/resilience). Requires error and overflow reporting useful for operation/monitoring (operability). No explicit availability, security, performance, scalability, portability, maintainability, legal, or UI requirements.
Specifies a concrete backend behavior for handling invalid data (replace with zeros) — this is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly address security, availability, performance, etc.

This requirement specifies a backend behavior: verifying that sent data was successfully received and reporting errors — a clear functional requirement (F). The instruction to report errors implies operational/monitoring concerns (O). It does not explicitly mention availability, fault-tolerance mechanisms (retries/recovery), security, maintainability, performance, scalability, portability, legal, UI/look-and-feel, or usability, so those labels are not set.

Specifies a recovery report feature (functional) describing results of recovery actions for internal components, which pertains to fault tolerance. Also supports operations/administration by providing recovery action results, so operability applies. No explicit availability, security, performance, scalability, portability, legal, maintainability, look-and-feel, or usability requirements.
This requirement specifies a functional behavior (the backend shall send output data to the end-to-end system). It does not state availability, performance, security, or other quality attributes.

Specifies a system capability to report internal component failures with an error number (translatable to text) and timestamp — this is a functional requirement. The requirement describes logging/diagnostic information useful for maintenance and administration, implying maintainability and operability.
Specifies the content/fields of a warning report (what the system should produce); no non-functional constraints (performance, security, availability, etc.) are mentioned.

Specifies a system capability to produce error reports with particular fields (functional). Such reporting supports system maintainability and operational monitoring/admin tasks, so Maintainability and Operability are also applicable. No explicit requirements about availability, fault recovery, performance, security, etc.

This statement specifies the content and presence of metadata to be recorded for processed time series and spectra (invalid data flags, processes applied, coordinates, etc.), which is a functional data requirement rather than a quality/constraint like security, performance, or usability.

Describes a data structure (table of processing flags) to identify internal conditions and error responses—this specifies what the system should provide (functional). No explicit non-functional aspects (availability, security, operability, etc.) are stated.

The requirement specifies a system capability to provide processing parameters (names, positions, adjustable parameters) for pipeline applications, which describes functional behavior/feature. It does not explicitly address availability, performance, security, maintainability, usability, or other non-functional aspects.

Describes data structures and behavior (memory buffer, status queue, contents for assembling lag sets) — a functional requirement. No explicit non-functional constraints like performance, availability, security, scalability, or portability are stated.

Requirement mandates BE processes be reversible and preserve raw input recoverability (functional behavior) and ensures data integrity/recoverability (security) and resilience/recoverability (fault tolerance). No explicit availability, legal, or other quality constraints are stated.

This requirement specifies a system capability to redistribute internal workload (functional). It implies fault-tolerance/resilience (FT) and scalability (SC) by enabling load redistribution across processors. It also affects operability (O) since it involves changing destination IPs and managing runtime redistribution. No explicit availability, performance, security, portability, legal, maintainability, look-and-feel, or usability constraints are stated.

The requirement specifies a backend capability to initiate a reboot of internal networks — this is a functional behavior. It also relates to system operation/administration (manageability/operability), so Operability is set. No explicit statements about availability, fault tolerance, security, portability, performance, scalability, maintainability, legal, look-and-feel, or usability.

Specifies an Output Data Queue (memory buffer + backup disk) and conversion/transfer behavior — a clear functional requirement. Backup disk storage implies resilience to failures (fault tolerance). A data entry status queue for tracking records pertains to operability/management. No explicit mentions of availability metrics, performance, security, scalability, portability, UI, maintainability, or legal aspects.

Requirement specifies system behavior to monitor and report data transfer rates (functional). It is clearly a monitoring/operational requirement (operability) and concerns performance metrics and tolerances (performance). No explicit mention of maintainability, availability targets, security, scalability, or other categories.

This requirement specifies a capability/behavior of the backend (ability to alter task priority), which is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly mention availability, security, performance, operability, or other non-functional aspects.
Specifies a capability (BE shall be able to signal kill) — functional. Also describes an administrative/manageability operation for backend processes — operability.
Requirement specifies a capability (initiate a processing task) — functional. Phrase 'on any Backend processor' indicates platform/environment compatibility, implying portability.

The requirement specifies a system behavior (periodically or on request check networks and report failures) so it's Functional. It explicitly concerns ensuring communication connections are intact — implying availability concerns. It describes monitoring/reporting which supports operability (administration/monitoring) and maintainability (detecting faults for maintenance). It does not require fault-tolerance, security, performance, portability, scalability, look-and-feel, legal, or usability aspects.

This requirement specifies a system behavior (periodically or on request check processors and report status) — functional. It describes monitoring/admin capability for operating and managing backend processors — operability. It does not specify recovery, uptime guarantees, security, performance, or other NFRs.

The requirement specifies a system behavior (periodically/on-request checking PIDs and reporting process states) so it is Functional. It describes monitoring capabilities which support system operability (administration/monitoring) and also aids maintainability (detecting broken processes for maintenance). It does not specify availability metrics, fault-tolerance recovery actions, security, performance, portability, scalability, legal, look-and-feel, or usability concerns.

Requirement specifies functional behavior (monitor, trap, flag, repair computation errors, accumulate statistics, compare to tolerances, report out-of-tolerance) => Functional. Explicit error handling and recovery imply Fault Tolerance. Accumulating error statistics and reporting supports maintenance/diagnosis => Maintainability. Monitoring and reporting are operational concerns for administrators => Operability. No explicit statements about availability, performance, security, portability, scalability, usability, look-and-feel, or legal compliance.

Requirement specifies a behavior (monitor data processing rate and report out-of-tolerance conditions) → Functional. It concerns measuring processing rate and tolerances → Performance. It describes monitoring/reporting for operations/administration → Operability. No mention of availability percentages, fault recovery, security, portability, scalability, UI, legal, or maintainability.

This is a functional requirement (ability to initiate reboot of a backend/physical processor). It also relates to operability/admin functions (administration/management capability). No explicit mention of security, availability, fault-tolerance, or other qualities.

Specifies what the MCCC shall be/capable of (functional). Explicitly requires high-availability, hot-swappable/redundant CPU and self-healing (availability and fault tolerance). Requires support for COTS operating systems (portability/OS compatibility). Hot-swappable/redundant capability implies operability (ease of administration/maintenance). No explicit performance, security, legal, usability, scalability, or maintainability requirements.

Req states OS/module must support real-time requirements (performance) and support test-bench operation and network-based access/upgrades (functional capabilities). Specifying support for platform features and network-based management implies operability. Ability to access/upgrade hardware personalities implies maintainability. No explicit availability, fault-tolerance, security, portability, scalability, legal, look-and-feel or usability requirements.

This requirement specifies hardware and interface/deployment constraints (memory, buses, I/O, network, ability to boot a COTS OS) which are deployment/operability concerns -> Operability. The 'near real-time environment' and boot/run performance imply performance constraints -> Performance. The need to run a generic COTS OS from local storage implies compatibility/portability considerations -> Portability. It does not state functional behavior, security, availability, scalability, or UI/look-and-feel, so those are not marked.

Requirement specifies conformance to electrical and physical PC104+ standards (hardware form factor/compatibility). This is a technical standards compliance about platform/physical compatibility (portability). It is not a legal/regulatory mandate nor a functional behavior, so only Portability is set.

Requirement specifies a functional capability (control of hardware warm boots and an external reboot command option) and describes an operational/administrative feature (ability for external command to force reboot). It does not explicitly address availability, fault tolerance, security, or other quality attributes.

Specifies ability for authorized users to remotely access systems (functional capability). Emphasizes access restricted to authorized users (security). Describes maintenance and monitoring via remote logins, which pertains to system operability/administration.

This requirement specifies a system capability/feature (support for multiple opening positions applicable to all games), which is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly state availability, performance, security, usability, scalability, or other non-functional concerns.

Specifies that the system must be fully usable via keyboard-only interaction, which is an accessibility/usability requirement (ease of use for keyboard users). No other quality attributes are implied.
Specifies a feature: the system provides an AI opponent that can play any two-player game. This describes functional behavior; no non-functional qualities are mentioned.

This specifies a system capability/feature (support two-player turn-based gaming), which is a functional requirement. No availability, performance, scalability, security, usability, or other quality constraints are mentioned.

Specifies a functional capability: an embedded AI that takes control from a player on request. No explicit non-functional constraints (availability, performance, security, UI/look-and-feel, etc.) are mentioned.

The requirement specifies a system capability (ability to define new games) — a functional aspect. The phrase 'without modifying the source code' indicates configurability/extensibility, which relates to maintainability. It also implies administrative/manageability (operators can add games), so operability is marked. No explicit mention of performance, security, scalability, portability, UI look-and-feel, or legal concerns.

The text specifies concrete API operations the framework must provide (create/delete/modify entities and relationships, list/access, execute queries) — this is functional behavior. It also specifies an exposed API interface to client processes, which relates to system operability/integration (how other components operate with it), so Operability is marked. No explicit mentions of availability, performance, security, portability, scalability, maintainability, legal, or UI/look-and-feel constraints.

Requirement specifies GUI design to mimic Windows applications and be instinctive to Windows users — this is about look-and-feel and usability. It does not mandate OS runtime, performance, security, or other qualities.

The statement prescribes an operational mode (single-user, no networking), which is a behavioral constraint (functional). It explicitly restricts multi-user/networked operation, directly impacting scalability (cannot scale to multiple users) and relates to how the system is operated/deployed (operability). It does not mention availability, fault tolerance, security, usability, portability, legal, performance, look-and-feel, or maintainability.

This requirement specifies a resource usage limit (memory <= 40 MB), which is a performance/resource constraint, so it maps to Performance. No functional behavior or other quality attributes are implied.

Requirement demands protection against malicious scripts (prevention of unauthorized access and integrity protection) which maps to Security (SE). The need to guard against unintended corruption by users implies mechanisms for resilience/recovery or protective controls (e.g., validation, undo, transaction safety), which aligns with Fault Tolerance (FT). No explicit availability, legal, usability, or functional behavior beyond security was stated.
This statement is a legal/trademark attribution covering ownership and rights; it addresses legal compliance/attribution rather than functional behavior or other quality attributes.

Requirement mandates conformance to an external standard (Windows 2000 Logo Requirements), which is a compliance/legal constraint. It does not explicitly state functional behavior, portability, or other quality attributes.
Specifies a functional constraint: the system shall have no communication interfaces at this stage. Does not explicitly address availability, security, or other quality attributes.

The requirement specifies that the online help use non-technical terms and avoid exhaustive documentation to serve users—this is a usability/UX concern (clarity, learnability). No explicit constraints about performance, availability, security, portability, maintainability, or look-and-feel are stated, and the optional developer guide does not explicitly imply other NFRs.

This requirement specifies functional capabilities: a GUI that can browse framework-managed information and allow users to specify relationships between Entities (Functional = true). It also explicitly constrains the GUI to be similar to Windows Explorer, which pertains to look-and-feel/layout requirements (LF = true). It does not mention availability, fault tolerance, performance, scalability, security, portability, maintainability, operability, or explicit usability/accessibility concerns, so those labels are set to false. Usability is only implied indirectly by the Explorer-like requirement, but not stated explicitly, so it was conservatively set to false.

The statement requires provisions for third-party applications to take advantage of the Framework (integration/compatibility/interoperability). This is a portability/compatibility requirement rather than a specific functional behavior or other quality attribute.

Specifies functional behavior of the system when entities are archived (how lookups should respond), so is Functional. It also concerns informing the user and optional remount action, which impacts usability (user feedback/interaction), hence Usability. No explicit availability, security, performance, or other quality attributes are mentioned.

Requirement mandates documenting and strictly following coding conventions, which primarily targets maintainability (code consistency, readability, and ease of future changes). No availability, performance, security, or UI aspects are implied.

Specifies distribution & website features (functional requirements) and distribution/hosting (operability). Stating it must be free and likely open-source implies licensing/legal constraint. Provision for user comments/wish-list impacts usability.
Specifies licensing under LGPL and GPL, which are legal/compliance constraints; no functional or other quality attributes implied.

Specifies conformance to character encoding standards (Unicode UTF-8/UTF-16), which is primarily about portability/interoperability across platforms and clients. Does not impose legal/regulatory constraints, performance, security, or UI requirements.

Requirement specifies system behavior (ability to archive to removable media while retaining knowledge of archived items) — functional. It also implies resilience when data is moved to removable storage (framework must not forget or lose references), which is a fault-tolerance/recovery concern. Other quality categories are not explicitly indicated.

MTBF is a reliability metric specifying time between failures, which directly relates to availability and implies fault tolerance/reliability requirements. It does not specify functional behavior or other quality attributes.

Requirement describes a system capability: automatically saving documents with relationships and allowing users to fetch documents by following relationship paths. This is a functional behavior (storage and retrieval). It does not explicitly specify availability, performance, security, usability, or other non-functional aspects.

Specifies a user capability (view hierarchical information) -> Functional. Describes UI presentation similar to Windows Explorer and GUI integration -> Look & Feel. Emphasis on user-facing presentation/usability -> Usability. No explicit availability, performance, security, portability, scalability, maintainability, or fault-tolerance requirements.

Requirement specifies functionality: capturing information from specified tools and storing it (centralized store, choice of entity/associate). It does not explicitly state availability, performance, security, scalability, operability, maintainability, portability, legal, look-and-feel, or usability constraints, so only Functional is set.
Specifies user capabilities to modify/add/delete/group entities via navigation—describes functional behavior (CRUD). No quality attributes like usability, performance, security, etc., are implied.

This statement specifies a processing behavior (emails must be intercepted prior to being sent to SMTP), which is a functional requirement. No explicit quality concerns (security, performance, availability, etc.) are stated.
Specifies creation of an entity ('Associate') to contain the message body — a functional behavior/data requirement. No quality/constraint aspects indicated.
Specifies system behavior: creating People entities from recipient names and linking an Associate—this is a functional requirement. No non-functional qualities are mentioned.

This statement specifies a behavior the system must perform (fetch email from a POP3 server), so it is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly address availability, security, portability, or other quality attributes.

This requirement specifies functional behavior: the Address Book shall create Entities under categories (with user-definable category names and some mandatory categories). It describes what the system must do rather than performance, security, usability, or other quality attributes.

Describes a functional behavior: creating an Entity of category 'People' from the sender's name and linking an Associate to that Entity. No availability, performance, security, UI, or other quality attributes are specified.

This requirement specifies a user capability (ability to specify when to start a research project and trigger permanent storage of visited websites), which is a functional behavior. It does not state availability, performance, security, usability, or other quality constraints.

The statement describes a functional behavior: when a user specifies a project name, the system creates (spawns) a new Entity in the Framework. It does not mention availability, performance, security, usability, or other non-functional concerns.
Describes a functional behavior/data model operation (creating an associate as an archive and linking it to an entity). No non-functional qualities (availability, security, UI, etc.) are implied.

Specifies a user action and system behavior (invoking a special GUI) — functional. Also references a GUI supplied by the Framework, implying interface/visual aspect (Look & Feel). No explicit non-functional attributes like performance, security, availability, etc.

Specifies a GUI feature/behavior (ability to draw arrows to create relationships) — a functional requirement describing what the system should do. No explicit non-functional constraints (performance, security, availability, etc.).

This requirement specifies a system capability (allowing the user to optionally provide a descriptive document name), which is a functional behavior. It does not impose availability, performance, security, usability, or other non-functional constraints.

Specifies mandatory use of a particular database engine (Microsoft SQL Server). This is a portability/platform constraint (PO) and also affects operation/administration since using the corporate standard influences deployment and operational practices (O). It does not explicitly state performance, security, availability, maintainability, or other qualities.
Requirement restricts UI complexity and learning curve for an infrequent task, which pertains to look & feel and usability characteristics rather than functional behavior or other NFRs.

The statement specifies the database should allow modification without large overhaul, which directly concerns maintainability (ease of modification/extensibility). It does not specify availability, performance, security, UI, portability, or other qualities.

Specifies access policy allowing public access without authentication, which is a security/authentication requirement. No performance, availability, usability, or other quality attributes are implied.

The requirement defines a user category and explicitly states they must not access password-protected sensitive data due to agency-level confidentiality. This is an access control/confidentiality constraint, i.e., a security requirement. It does not specify functional behavior beyond access restriction nor other quality attributes.

Specifies a user role and explicit read/write/modify privileges to all data—this concerns access control/authorization and therefore security. No mention of availability, performance, portability, UI, maintainability, or other qualities.
Specifies that only staff in watersheds with responsibility should have write access to allocated space — an access control/authorization requirement (security).

Specifies a system operator role that must have full access to the system — this is an access-control/security requirement (SE) and relates to system administration/operability (O). It also explicitly ties to maintaining executable code, implying maintainability concerns (MN). No explicit statements about availability, performance, portability, scalability, look-and-feel, legal, fault-tolerance, or usability.

The requirement specifies use of standard hardware, network connections, servers, and management tools at a specific operations/hosting center, which concerns system operation, deployment and manageability. It does not state uptime targets, performance, portability, security, or other quality attributes explicitly.

Specifies a dedicated back-end private network to prevent back-end data transfers from impeding front-end operations — this addresses availability/reliability of service and performance (latency/throughput) concerns.

This is a compliance requirement referring to applicable policies (Legal). It explicitly mentions Security policies (SE), Accessibility (affects Usability), and Web Design (affects Look & Feel), so L, SE, US, and LF are marked.

The text specifies that ARS users require user/password authentication and access control for data protected by confidentiality agreements — this implies a functional requirement (authentication and user settings) and security (access control/confidentiality). Mention of data protected by agreements suggests legal/compliance constraints. No explicit references to availability, performance, scalability, portability, fault tolerance, maintainability, operability, look-and-feel, or usability are present.

This requirement specifies a development/process artifact (documenting a testing plan during the Design phase) and how testing will be structured. It is a maintainability/process-related requirement about assuring correct testing and future verification, not a functional feature or other quality attribute, so Maintainability is applicable.

Specifies required use/integration with Microsoft SQL Server as the corporate standard primary data storage mechanism—this is about system operation/administration and integration with an external DBMS (operability). It does not state performance, portability, security, or other quality constraints.

The requirement specifies provision of an online help system that describes and illustrates all system functions — this is a functional requirement (F). It also targets user assistance/experience (hierarchical, cross-linked help in HTML), which impacts usability (US). It does not explicitly state availability, performance, security, portability, maintainability, operability, scalability, fault-tolerance, or legal constraints, so those labels are not set.

The requirement describes specific system capabilities: an online form for users to request help and screening FAQs for the FAQ pages. These are functional features (what the system should do). No quality/constraints such as availability, performance, security, usability, or others are specified.

This requirement specifies a user guide/manual with instructions, system overview, and sample screens—aimed at helping users understand and use the system (usability). Inclusion of sample screens and overview of features implies concerns about presentation/appearance consistent with Look & Feel. It does not specify availability, security, performance, portability, scalability, maintainability, operability, or legal constraints.

The statement defines a system function — managing data and application backups via supported backup software (functional). It also implies resilience/recovery capability (fault tolerance). No explicit mention of availability metrics, operability/support processes, security, maintainability, scalability, portability, or UI aspects, so those are not set.

Specifies required server technology (HTTP and GIS server applications) as infrastructure for delivering the application, which pertains to operability/administration. Does not specify availability, performance, security, portability, or functional behavior.

Specifies use of commonly supported web browsers for a thin-client (portability/compatibility across browsers) and relates to how the system is accessed/implemented (operability). It does not explicitly state security, usability, performance, or other qualities.

The requirement specifies that email server applications must be supported as a secondary delivery protocol, which concerns the system's ability to operate with/against external email services (operability). It also implies compatibility with various email server applications/environments (portability). It does not specify functional behaviors in detail, availability, security, performance, or other quality attributes explicitly, so those are not set.

Specifies required use of standard software resources and supported platforms/servers (e.g., MS SQL/IIS, Apache/MySQL), which impacts operability (deployment/administration) and portability/compatibility across supported environments. No explicit performance, security, availability, or other quality requirements stated.

The statement specifies a system function: making data available in standardized formats (functional). It emphasizes interoperability with client/off-line applications (portability). Requiring standard formats for use by client systems also relates to operability/manageability (ease of integrating with client tools), so O is marked. No indications of availability, security, performance, scalability, maintainability, legal, look-and-feel, or usability requirements.

Requirement describes the user interface’s appearance/consistency and use of standard terminology (Look & Feel) and emphasizes ease of use, intuitiveness, elimination of training, and user testing to ensure clarity and completeness (Usability). It does not specify functional behavior, performance, security, availability, portability, scalability, maintainability, or operability.

The requirement specifies functional behavior (warning on low transmission speed, non-graphical interface) so F=1. It constrains deployment to standard hardware/resources provided by the hosting site, which is a portability/deployment constraint (PO=1). It addresses operational/deployment environment and use of network resources, implying operability/management concerns (O=1). Offering a non-graphical interface relates to usability/accessibility (US=1). Other quality categories are not explicitly implied.

Specifies which communications resources/protocols and operational environment (use of ARS OCIO, HTTP/TCP-IP) rather than functional behavior or other quality attributes; aligns with operability/operation requirements.

The statement explicitly requires load balancing to ensure maximum stability and availability (Availability=A) and mentions fail-over scenarios (Fault Tolerance=FT). Load balancing implies handling increased load and throughput, and supports scaling (Scalability=SC) and performance (PE). It does not state functional behavior beyond NFRs, nor legal, UI, maintainability, portability, security, or usability concerns, so those are set to false.

This requirement specifies that the system will provide a tutorial (a functional capability). It also strongly implies an emphasis on user assistance and learnability, so usability is applicable. No explicit availability, performance, security, portability, scalability, maintainability, legal, look-and-feel, or fault-tolerance concerns are stated.

Requirement specifies regular backups and off-site secure storage with a 24-hour retrieval time. This implies fault tolerance/recovery (FT), specifies an availability/retrieval time objective (A), and requires secure handling of data (SE). It does not state functional behavior, maintainability, operability, performance, portability, scalability, legal, look-and-feel, or usability aspects explicitly.

Specifies required/standard software platforms and servers to be used (databases, web servers, languages) which affects operability/administration and compatibility across environments. Does not state performance, security, availability, or UI requirements.

Specifies implementation of a database and browse/query functionality (functional). Similar database-related requirements in examples were labeled Maintainability and Operability, as it concerns data storage and system operation/administration; no explicit mentions of performance, security, availability, scalability, portability, legal, look-and-feel, or usability.

Requirement specifies the system must store hundreds of MB (potentially GB) on demand—this indicates a functional capability (storage) and implies capacity/performance constraints and need to scale to larger storage. No explicit availability, security, fault-tolerance, portability, or usability requirements are stated.

This requirement specifies a capability the system must provide (establish a database to house research data), so it is Functional. It describes storage of collective and varied data types which relates to data management concerns and long-term storage—aligning with Maintainability. Setting up and supporting a database implies operational/administrative responsibilities (operability). No explicit statements about availability, performance, scalability, security, portability, legal, look-and-feel, or usability are given.

The text specifies core system behaviors: providing measured data as model inputs and comparison to outputs, and reporting/maintenance of uncertainty information — these are functional requirements. The mention of 'maintenance and reporting' implies processes for maintaining data and its metadata, which aligns with maintainability. It does not explicitly mention availability, security, performance, portability, scalability, operability, look-and-feel, legal, or usability concerns.

Requirement describes functional capability (view/select watersheds and navigation tools). It references a top-level screen and navigation/design tools, implying UI layout/appearance and usability concerns (ease of navigation), but not availability, performance, security, etc.

The requirement specifies that users should be able to view/access descriptive and summary information (a clear functional need). The phrasing 'should be accessible' refers to user access/usability of the information rather than system uptime or security, so Usability is also applicable. No explicit availability SLAs, security, or other non-functional concerns are stated.

The requirement specifies system capabilities (browsing, querying, metadata search, downloading) — functional. It also emphasizes simple queries and user-facing access methods (browsing, search tools), implying usability concerns, so US is set. No explicit availability, security, performance, scalability, portability, or other non-functional aspects are stated.

Requirement specifies a functional capability (examining time-series data and selecting for download) and mentions charting tools (presentation/UI), implying look-and-feel and usability concerns. No explicit availability, performance, security, scalability, portability, maintainability, operability, or fault-tolerance constraints are stated.

This statement specifies a system capability (providing access to reports, tables, and documents), i.e. a functional requirement. It does not mention authorization, availability, performance, or other quality constraints.

Specifies functional capabilities: web-based GIS tools, browse/query features, and download links for spatial and tabular data. No explicit non-functional constraints (availability, performance, security, usability, etc.) are stated.

This requirement specifies building (functional behavior) a metadata database and tools to provide browse/query access and upload capabilities — clearly functional. It also implies operational/management capabilities (tools for contributors, maintenance of the database), so Operability is set. It does not explicitly state availability, fault tolerance, performance, security, portability, scalability, look-and-feel, or maintainability qualities, so those labels are not set.

This requirement specifies a functional capability: search/query tools for metadata with specific query types (location, theme, keyword). It describes what the system should do, not availability, performance, security, or other quality attributes.

Specifies which web browsers the system must operate with, focusing on operational compatibility/administration. Matches examples labeling similar browser-support requirements as Operability. Does not explicitly state portability or other quality attributes.

Specifies required operational environment (certified/accredited servers and corporate-approved OS versions) which affects operability (deployment/administration) and portability/compatibility across platforms; no explicit availability, security, performance, or other quality attributes mentioned.

Specifies allowed access locations (intranet and authorized Internet access through firewall) — this is a functional requirement about permitting access and explicitly involves authorization/network access control, i.e., a security constraint.

The requirement specifies user capabilities (examine data, visualize spatial results, download inputs/results), which are functional features. It does not specify availability, performance, security, UI aesthetics, or other quality attributes.

The requirement describes that code generated during prototyping may not run on a non-Windows OS or when moved to another location, which is a portability concern (compatibility across platforms/environments). No other quality attributes are explicitly implied.

Describes a functional feature (web-based browse-and-query tool, supported query types, wizard, saving queries). Also specifies ease-of-use/minimal training and a wizard interface, which implies usability requirements. No explicit performance, security, availability, scalability, portability, legal, maintainability, operability, or look-and-feel constraints.

The requirement specifies a capability to create/edit metadata, save and reuse selections and a web-based wizard—these are functional requirements. The mention of a wizard and user-oriented input implies usability concerns (ease of use), so US is set. No explicit non-functional attributes like availability, security, performance, scalability, portability, or maintainability are stated.

This statement specifies a system capability (providing public access to reviewed and approved data sets), which is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly state availability, security, performance, or other non-functional constraints.

The requirement explicitly mandates compliance with Federal metadata standards (FGDC/ISO), which is a legal/regulatory compliance constraint. It does not state functional behavior, performance, security, usability, or other quality attributes.

Explicitly specifies 24/7 availability and 99% target (availability requirement). Also discusses reliability of software/network components and tolerance, implying fault-tolerance/resilience requirements.

The requirement explicitly addresses confidentiality and protecting data, specifying user classes and restricted access and 'appropriate security features'—this maps directly to security concerns (access control, confidentiality). No explicit availability, performance, usability, or other quality attributes are stated.

The requirement focuses on ensuring data integrity via validation, review, and policies/procedures to prevent intentional or unintentional modification. This primarily maps to Security (data integrity controls) and Maintainability (ongoing validation/review processes and procedures that support correct data management). Other NFRs are not explicitly implied.

Requirement mandates compliance with agency/Dept/Govt regulations and ARS OCIO practices (legal/compliance). It explicitly enumerates security components—authentication, confidentiality, integrity, and availability—so security is applicable, and availability is explicitly mentioned as a primary component. No functional behavior or other quality attributes are specified.

Requirement specifies protecting server data against power loss (durability/availability) and describes monitoring and retrying uploads on failure (fault tolerance/resilience and operational monitoring). It does not specify security, portability, performance, or functional behavior beyond these quality aspects.

This requirement specifies load speed relative to comparable productivity tools across environments, which is a performance (speed/latency) requirement. It does not explicitly address availability, portability, usability, scalability, or other categories.

Specifies response time targets and behavior as load (number of persons) increases — primary performance requirement. The clause about no visible deterioration with increasing users implies scalability.

Specifies portability characteristics: database itself may not be portable but query results will be portable across environments. This directly concerns portability; no explicit functional, performance, security, or other quality requirements are stated.

Requirement specifies that the system will perform authentication (functional behavior) and emphasizes security best practices and authentication mechanisms (single-sign-on, Active Directory) to ensure users are who they claim to be, so Security is clearly applicable. No explicit availability, performance, maintainability, or other NFRs are stated.

Specifying RAID5 disk striping for database storage is a storage-availability and resilience requirement (RAID provides fault tolerance and improves uptime) and also impacts performance (throughput/IO). It does not specify functional behavior, security, legal, UI, portability, scalability, or usability explicitly.

Requirement mandates database replication to off-site locations which is a provided system capability (functional) aimed at improving availability and enabling fault tolerance/disaster recovery. No mention of security, scalability, or other qualities.

Requirement specifies redundant storage and automatic switchover, which directly addresses availability and fault tolerance (redundancy and automatic failover). It does not state functional behavior, security, performance, scalability, or other attributes.

Requirement specifies browser compatibility (Internet Explorer, Mozilla, Netscape), which is portability across client environments. It does not state functional behavior, performance, security, or other quality attributes.

Specifies that source code must be maintained in a configuration management tool, which is a maintainability/process requirement (version control/configuration management). Does not describe functional behavior or other quality attributes explicitly.

Specifies required communication protocols for operation (HTTP for internet, TCP/IP for intranet), which is an operational/deployment constraint. Does not specify functional behavior, security, performance, or portability explicitly.

Requirement specifies functionality: enable users to complete transactions (functional). It emphasizes 'secured transaction' and likening to Verisign/third-party security software, which implies security requirements (confidentiality/integrity/authentication). No explicit mentions of availability, performance, scalability, portability, legal, or other qualities.

This is primarily a functional requirement (the system shall communicate with an external export-regulation system). It also implies legal/compliance concerns because it exists to validate export regulations, and it involves integration/operability with an external system, so Operability is applicable. No explicit statements about availability, performance, portability, security, scalability, maintainability, look-and-feel, fault-tolerance, or usability.

This is primarily a functional requirement specifying integration with an external Tax system (what the system should do). It also implies operability/interoperability concerns (ability to communicate with external systems), but does not mention availability, security, portability, or other quality attributes.

This is primarily a functional requirement (system must communicate with shipping system). It also implies operability/ integration concerns (managing interfaces), but does not explicitly state availability, portability, security, or performance constraints.

Requirement specifies a functional capability (communication with Sales system) — therefore Functional. It describes an integration/interaction concern relevant to system operations/administration (interfacing with another system), so Operability is applicable. No explicit availability, performance, portability, security, scalability, or other quality constraints are stated.

This is primarily a functional integration requirement (system shall communicate with CRM). It also implies operability/integ­rability concerns (manage/operate interfaces), but no explicit availability, security, scalability, portability, or UI requirements.

This requirement specifies a system behavior (communicate with credit management system) — functional. It also implies integration/operability concerns (interfacing with an external system), but does not state availability, performance, security, portability, or other quality attributes.

Specifies operational behavior: communicating with billPay to identify payment methods, validate and process payments — a functional integration requirement. No explicit availability, security, performance, or other quality constraints mentioned.

This sentence specifies a system behavior/interface (the e-store shall communicate with the content manager to retrieve product data), which is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly state availability, performance, security, portability, or other non-functional aspects.

Requirement specifies a functional behavior (system shall communicate with Configurator to identify components). It does not state availability, performance, security, portability, or other quality attributes.

Requirement specifies required hardware interfaces for internet connectivity (modem, WAN/LAN, Ethernet), which concerns deployment/operational environment and manageability. This aligns with Operability. It does not state functional behavior or portability, performance, security, etc.

This requirement constrains implementation technologies/platforms for the user interface (mentions Java Applet, MS FrontPage, EJB), which is primarily a portability/implementation constraint. It does not specify functional behavior, usability, performance, security, or other quality attributes.

Specifies that the system shall have a logical address in IPv4 format — a functional requirement describing what the system must provide. No explicit non-functional qualities (availability, security, etc.) are stated.

Specifies a deployment/configuration detail (network port) relevant to system operation and environment compatibility. This affects operability and may impact portability (firewall/hosting constraints). No explicit performance, security, or functional behavior stated.

Specifying the communication protocol (HTTP) is an operational/deployment constraint about how the system is accessed and operated, not a functional behavior or other quality attribute. It does not explicitly address availability, security, portability, etc.

The statement specifies what the system should support (types of interfaces: user, software, hardware), which is a functional capability. It does not specify quality attributes like availability, security, usability, portability, or look-and-feel, so no other labels are set.

The requirement mandates that the system provide online user help via links and search fields — this is a functional provision (F). It also specifies UI elements (links/search) which affects look-and-feel (LF) and supports usability (US) by enabling users to find help.

Requirement specifies providing user guidance/help within the system, which affects usability and aspects of look-and-feel (how instructions are presented). It does not describe availability, security, performance, etc.

The statement specifies that an online help system shall be provided (functional requirement). It also implies a usability concern since online help is intended to assist users and improve usability. No explicit references to availability, security, performance, scalability, maintainability, legal, look-and-feel, portability, operability, or fault tolerance are present.

The requirement specifies a user prerequisite about needed skills to use the product, which pertains to usability and user competence. It does not describe functionality, performance, security, or other NFRs.
Specifies a maximum allowable response time (loading the product within five minutes), which is a performance requirement/quality-of-service metric.

The statement mandates that computers be equipped with web browsers (deployment/environment requirement) which relates to operability (installed software on workstations). It also implies a platform/browser dependency/compatibility requirement (portability). No security, performance, or other qualities are mentioned.

The requirement mandates conformance to IBM CUA or Microsoft GUI standards for the web UI—this explicitly concerns the user interface look-and-feel. It does not explicitly state availability, security, portability, maintainability, or other quality attributes.

The requirement specifies a system behavior — it must display specific notices — so it is functional. It also explicitly concerns legal/copyright/trademark and warranties, implying legal/compliance constraints. It does not specify availability, performance, UI style, security, portability, scalability, maintainability, operability or usability aspects.

The requirement specifies that storage must enable the client to easily access the product, which is a usability/accessibility quality. It does not specify functional behavior, availability, performance, security, or other NFRs explicitly, so only Usability is marked.
