Specifies features to provide online help, FAQs, customer support and sitemap—this is a functional requirement. It also implies usability concerns (help/FAQ improve user experience). No mention of availability, security, performance, scalability, or other NFRs.
Requirement specifies a functional behavior: displaying matching products in search results. It does not mention availability, performance, usability, security, or other non-functional concerns.

This requirement specifies a functional capability—allowing a user to confirm completion of a configuration. It does not mention availability, performance, security, usability, or other quality attributes.

The statement specifies a system capability (allow user to update configuration to resolve conflicts), which is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly state availability, security, performance, usability, maintainability, or other non-functional aspects.

This requirement specifies a system behavior: displaying all available product components for configuration. It is a functional requirement and does not mention availability, performance, security, usability, or other non-functional concerns.

This requirement specifies a functional behavior (display reviews and ratings when a product is selected). It does not state any non-functional qualities such as performance, security, availability, usability, or appearance.
Specifies a user-facing capability (allow user to change shipping and payment method), i.e., a functional requirement. No quality attributes (availability, security, performance, etc.) are implied.
This requirement specifies a functional capability (allow user to cancel an order). It does not mention availability, performance, security, usability, or other non-functional concerns.

Describes a specific capability (command emergency stop for all trains in an area or a specific train) — a functional requirement. It does not explicitly state availability, security/authorization, fault-tolerance, scalability, usability, or other non-functional concerns.

This specifies that the system shall indicate the train trip operation on the Driver-Machine Interface (DMI), which is a functional requirement about what the system must do. It does not specify availability, performance, security, or UI aesthetics/usability details.

This specifies a functional capability: the system must allow commanding an immediate train stop. It does not explicitly mention availability, safety, fault tolerance, security, or other quality attributes.

Specifies system behavior: ability to command a conditional emergency stop and the condition under which the command is ignored (train passed location). This describes functional requirements (what the system should do) rather than non-functional qualities.

This specifies a required system behavior: upon receiving an emergency stop signal, ETCS must command the emergency brake. It is a functional requirement describing what the system shall do; it does not state non-functional qualities like availability, performance, security, etc.

This requirement specifies a functional behavior: the system shall indicate the emergency stop to the driver via the DMI (display). It does not explicitly state non-functional qualities such as usability, performance, availability, etc.

This is a functional requirement specifying that the system must indicate route unsuitability on the DMI (display). It does not explicitly state availability, performance, UI look-and-feel, usability metrics, security, or other non-functional concerns.
Specifies an actor capability (driver can override a function under a condition) — a functional requirement. No explicit non-functional qualities (availability, safety, operability, etc.) are stated.

This requirement specifies required system behavior (re-establish movement authority after overriding a function) — functional. It also implies recovery/resilience after an intervention, i.e. fault-tolerance/recovery, so FT is set. No explicit availability, security, portability, etc. requirements are stated.

This specifies a required system behavior in response to an event (functional). It also describes a safety/fault-handling action (trigger emergency brake) implying fault-tolerance/resilience, so FT is marked. No indications of other quality attributes.

This specifies a functional behavior: the trainborne equipment must transmit its train identification to the RBC. No non-functional qualities (availability, security, performance, etc.) are explicitly stated.

Specifies a system behavior: when stationary, driver must acknowledge trip condition and that acknowledgement releases the emergency brake. This describes functional behavior/requirement rather than non-functional qualities.

This statement specifies a system behavior (after acknowledgement, driver can continue movement), which is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly state availability, fault tolerance, performance, usability, or other quality attributes.

Specifies a system capability (train can be driven backwards a defined distance after acknowledgement) — this is a functional behavior. Although it references a 'national value', it does not explicitly state legal/regulatory compliance or other quality attributes.

This requirement specifies the format/structure of a data field (train running number) — a functional constraint on what the system should accept/store. It does not address availability, performance, security, usability, or other non-functional qualities.

This requirement specifies a functional behavior: the system shall indicate the train's front-end geographical position on the DMI on demand, and that it must work whether the train is moving or stationary. It does not state availability, performance, security, or other quality attributes explicitly.

Specifies a capability the on-board ETCS shall provide (receiving pantograph and power supply info from trackside) — a functional requirement. No quality attributes such as availability, performance, security, scalability, etc., are mentioned.

This requirement specifies a behavior: the equipment shall indicate (display) pantograph and power supply information on the DMI. It is a functional requirement about what the system should do. It does not state availability, performance, UI look-and-feel details, security, or other non-functional concerns.

Requirement specifies that information about pantograph and circuit breaker events must be provided (functional). It also prescribes how the information should be presented (separately and in combinations), which affects presentation/look-and-feel, so LF applies. No indications of other quality attributes.

This requirement specifies a capability the system must provide (receiving air tightness information from trackside), which is functional. It does not mention availability, performance, security, scalability, or other quality attributes.

Specifies system behavior (apply emergency brake until traction unit is stationary). This is a functional requirement; no explicit non-functional qualities (availability, fault tolerance, safety standards, etc.) are stated.

Specifies a capability the system (train) must provide: receiving track-to-train information (including movement authority). This describes functional behavior (what the system should do) rather than non-functional qualities like performance, availability, security, or scalability.

Requirement specifies that received information must not affect traction units when cabs are inoperative — this is a behavioral constraint (functional). It also addresses system behavior in a fault/failed condition (in-operative cabs), implying fault-tolerance/resilience. Finally it constrains operational behavior/controls of the system (operability). No explicit availability, security, legal, UI, performance, portability, scalability, maintainability, or usability aspects are mentioned.

Specifies that a particular indication must be shown on the DMI (a UI/display requirement) — a functional requirement with a user interface presentation aspect; no availability, performance, security, or other quality attributes are mentioned.

The requirement specifies a capability (sending plain text messages from track to train), which is a functional behavior. It does not state availability, performance, security, portability, or other quality constraints, so no NFR labels are warranted.

Specifies a behavior: the system shall indicate roll away/reverse movement intervention on the DMI (display). This is a functional requirement about what must be shown. No non-functional qualities (availability, security, performance, usability, look-and-feel) are explicitly required.

Specifies a concrete system behavior: when the traction unit is stationary, the driver must be able to release the emergency brake. This is a functional requirement describing what the system shall allow the user to do.

This specifies a functional behavior: after emergency brake release the ETCS must provide the supervision related to the roll-away protection. No non-functional aspects (availability, performance, security, etc.) are implied.

Specifies a functional behavior: when multiple traction units are used, the function must be disabled on all but the leading unit. No availability, performance, security, or other non-functional attributes are mentioned.

The requirement explicitly mandates that all data entered/received/indicated to the driver be recorded onboard and timestamped relative to UTC/reference point — this specifies a required system function (logging/recording). It does not explicitly state security, availability, maintainability, or other quality constraints, so only Functional is set.

Requirement specifies that information shall be recorded (functional behavior). The emphasis on accuracy to enable a clear view of system functioning and traction unit driving implies an operational/monitoring concern (operability). It does not explicitly state legal, performance, security, scalability, portability, look-and-feel, or maintainability attributes.

The requirement specifies a capability (standardised output interfaces to transmit recorded information) which is a functional behavior. It also implies portability/interoperability with other media (compatibility), so Portability is set. No explicit indications of availability, security, performance, scalability, maintainability, look-and-feel, or operability/administration concerns.

This requirement specifies operational data management (data retention periods and storage duration), which is an operability/administration concern. It does not invoke legal compliance, security, performance, or UI aspects, nor a functional feature beyond storage durations.

The requirement specifies that various events and data must be recorded—this is a functional requirement (F) describing system behavior. Recording/auditing of actions also supports maintainability (MN) by providing trace/history for diagnosis and change tracking. It also supports operability (O) because captured operational events and supervision data are used for monitoring and operating the system. No explicit statements about availability, fault tolerance, security controls, legal compliance, performance, portability, scalability, look-and-feel, or usability are present.

The requirement specifies a system capability/behavior: allowing use of multiple traction units without isolating ETCS equipment when a cab is inoperative — this is a functional requirement. It also addresses resilience to a fault condition (in-operative cab) by requiring continued operation, which implies fault tolerance. No explicit statements about availability metrics, security, usability, maintainability, portability, scalability, look & feel, or operability/administration are given.

This specifies a system behavior: the 'train trip function' must be suppressed when traction unit cabs are inoperative. It is a functional constraint/condition rather than an availability, safety, or other non-functional requirement.

The statement specifies a capability the system must provide (use tandem traction units without isolating ETCS equipment), which is a functional requirement. It also pertains to the operational use of the equipment (how units are operated/managed), so Operability is relevant. It does not mention availability, performance, security, safety, or other quality attributes explicitly.

This requirement specifies that a particular function (train trip function 4.6.12) shall be suppressed on a specific unit (tandem traction unit), which is a functional behavior constraint. It does not mention availability, performance, security, portability, usability, or other non-functional concerns.
This specifies a functional action the system/user must perform (driver enters driver ID). No quality constraints (availability, security, performance, etc.) are mentioned.

Specifies a system capability/function: enabling supervised backward driving with control of speed and distance based on trackside information. No explicit non-functional quality (availability, security, performance, etc.) is stated.
Specifies required system behavior (limit train speed) — functional. Refers to a national-specified value, implying regulatory/legal compliance.

This is a functional requirement describing what the system/driver shall do (select an override control based on received permission). It does not explicitly state availability, security mechanisms, performance, or other non-functional concerns.

Requirement specifies that an override control must be protected from inadvertent operation — this is a usability requirement (preventing accidental actions) and also addresses fault tolerance/safety by guarding against operator error. It does not specify availability, security, portability, etc.

This requirement specifies a functional behavior: when a train passes a stop signal, the system shall suppress the train trip function. It describes what the system must do; it does not state any non-functional constraints (availability, performance, security, etc.).

This requirement specifies that the system must display the actual speed on the DMI (a functional behavior involving the user interface). It concerns the UI content/presentation, so Look & Feel is also applicable. No availability, performance, security, or other quality attributes are implied.

This requirement constrains what is displayed on the DMI (a user interface content/design restriction). It pertains to presentation/appearance of the interface rather than performance, security, or other quality attributes.
Specifies a system behavior: when a plain text message appears on the DMI, the system shall alert the driver. This is a functional requirement describing what the system must do (notification).

The text defines operational levels and behaviors of the ETCS application (Level 0,1,2,3, STM), specifying what the system does in each mode. This is a functional requirement; it does not specify availability, performance, security, or other non-functional qualities.

Requirement constrains character encoding to support multiple languages (internationalization). This is primarily a usability/internationalization concern and relates to portability across language environments/platforms. It does not specify functional behavior, performance, security, etc.

This requirement specifies a capability the system must provide (support implementing one or more ETCS application levels on a line) — a functional requirement. It also implies an operational/configurational concern (ability to deploy/configure application levels on a line), so operability is marked. No explicit reliability, security, performance, portability, scalability, maintainability, legal, look-and-feel, or usability aspects are stated.

Specifies that trains (system) must be able to operate on lines with different ERTMS/ETCS application levels — a functional capability combined with platform/environment compatibility (portability/interoperability). No availability, security, performance, or other quality attributes are mentioned.

This requirement specifies that the system shall indicate (display) the current application level on the DMI, which is a functional behavior (what the system should do). It does not state availability, fault tolerance, UI aesthetics, or other non-functional qualities explicitly.

This specifies required system behavior (control logic for driver acknowledgements and braking) — functional. It also defines behavior in presence of a failure/unresponsive driver (apply brake, allow release later), i.e., fault-handling/resilience, so Fault Tolerance applies.

Requirement specifies compatibility/interoperability with existing national systems to avoid mutual interference. This primarily concerns portability/compatibility across systems (PO) and operational interoperability/handling in the target environment (O). It does not explicitly address availability, security, performance, maintainability, or other categories.
Specifies system capability to supervise listed operational states (functional behavior/capability). No explicit non-functional constraints (availability, performance, security, etc.) are stated.

The requirement specifies a behavior: transitions that occur while the train is moving shall occur automatically. This describes what the system should do (functional). It does not explicitly state non-functional qualities such as availability, performance, safety, or fault tolerance, so other labels are not set.

Specifies system behavior: how transitions are initiated (automatic or manual) when the train is stationary, which is a functional requirement. Does not specify availability, performance, security, usability, or other quality attributes.

The requirement specifies a system behavior: when an automatic transition increases driver responsibility, the ETCS must seek driver acknowledgement. This is a functional behavior (user interaction/response). It does not explicitly state availability, fault tolerance, security, usability, or other quality attributes.

Specifies a system action: ETCS shall request an acknowledgement by the driver during specific transitions. This is a functional requirement; it does not explicitly state availability, security, usability, or other quality attributes.

Specifies system behavior: if driver fails to acknowledge a transition, ETCS shall apply brakes. This is a functional safety action; no explicit availability, performance, security, or other NFRs are stated.

The requirement specifies ensuring 'the same protection' during transitions between operational states/nations, which pertains to security/protection measures (confidentiality/integrity/authorization). It does not explicitly address availability, fault-tolerance, operability, or other non-functional categories, so only Security is marked.

Requirement specifies a system behavior: when a train passes to a line with multiple levels, the onboard shall switch to the highest applicable level according to trackside priority. This is a functional requirement describing what the system must do; it does not state availability, performance, security, or other non-functional constraints.

This specifies a required system behavior (initiate braking) when encountering an unsupported level — primarily a functional requirement. It also describes handling an abnormal condition by moving to a safe state, which is a fault-tolerance/resilience behavior.

This specifies a system behavior: displaying current operational status to the driver on the DMI (Functional requirement). It does not specify availability, UI appearance details, usability metrics, security, or other non-functional concerns.

This specifies a capability of the ETCS on-board system (receiving national values from trackside to adapt to national requirements), which is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly state availability, performance, security, scalability, portability, or other non-functional concerns.

The statement specifies a system capability/behavior — that national values are to be applicable to a defined area — which is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly mention availability, security, performance, legal compliance, usability, or other non-functional aspects.

Requirement specifies that onboard national values must remain valid despite the onboard equipment being switched off — this describes resilience/durability to power loss (graceful retention/recovery), which is fault-tolerance. It does not state uptime, security, UI, portability, or other qualities.

This requirement specifies system behavior (use default values when no valid national values exist) — functional. It also describes a resilience/backup behavior for missing data, implying fault tolerance/graceful degradation. No explicit availability, security, usability, portability, etc., are mentioned.

The statement specifies a functional requirement: default values shall be harmonised and permanently stored in all on-board equipment (i.e., what the system must do). It does not explicitly state availability, fault-tolerance, security, portability, performance, scalability, usability, legal, look-and-feel or maintainability concerns, so those are not marked.

This is primarily a functional requirement describing system behavior (apply emergency brake after a specified distance). It references a 'national value' (regulatory/normative parameter), which implies legal/regulatory constraint, so Legal is marked. No explicit statements about availability, performance, safety (beyond function), usability, maintainability, etc., are given.
Specifies a capability requirement (functional) that the system must operate up to a specified maximum train speed (500 km/h), which is also a performance constraint on operational envelope.

Requirement specifies behavior: the equipment shall display plain text messages as received. This is a functional display requirement; it does not impose availability, security, look-and-feel specifics beyond plaintext, or other quality attributes.

The requirement specifies system behavior: the RBC-supervised system must be able to prevent traction unit movements when not authorized (functional behavior). It also enforces authorization control (access/authorization restriction), which is a security requirement. No explicit mention of availability, fault tolerance, usability, portability, scalability, legal, maintainability, operability, performance, or look-and-feel.

This is primarily a functional requirement: the system shall provide information to the driver. It implies safety as a goal but does not state non-functional qualities (availability, performance, usability, security, etc.), so no other NFR labels are set.

This requirement specifies a system capability (sending fixed text messages from track to train), which is a functional behavior. It does not mention availability, performance, security, or other quality attributes.

Specifies functional behavior (system must provide fixed text messages in the language selected) and impacts usability (language selection affects user experience). No explicit availability, performance, security, legal, or other quality concerns mentioned.

The requirement specifies a capability to send information about inhibition for specific brake types, which is a functional behavior. It does not mention availability, security, performance, or other non-functional qualities.
Requirement specifies a functional behavior (displaying information on the DMI). It does not mention availability, performance, usability, or other quality attributes, so only Functional is set.

This requirement specifies a capability (ETCS on-board shall be capable of sending train integrity information to trackside), which is a functional behavior. It does not explicitly state non-functional aspects such as availability, performance, security, scalability, maintainability, etc.

This requirement specifies a capability the system must provide (driver manually confirming train integrity to the RBC) and a precondition (train must be stationary). It describes functional behavior rather than non-functional qualities such as availability, performance, security, or usability, so only Functional is set.

Specifies a capability/behavior: sending train data under specified conditions (after driver confirmation or when entering RBC area). No quality attributes (performance, security, availability, etc.) are mentioned.
Specifies what data items must be transmitted from onboard to trackside — a clear functional requirement. No availability, security, performance, or other quality constraints are mentioned.

This requirement specifies a concrete capability/behavior: the system must support revocation of an issued Movement Authority cooperatively between RBC and train — a functional behavior. It does not explicitly state availability, fault tolerance, security, usability, or other quality attributes, so no other labels are set.

This requirement specifies a capability/behavior ('co-operative revocation of the MA shall be possible to a new target location, proposed from RBC'), which is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly state reliability/availability, fault-tolerance, security, usability, or other quality attributes, so no other labels are set.

This is a statement of system behavior: the system must perform a check that a new target location is accepted by the onboard component. It specifies a functional action (validation/acceptance check). No explicit quality attributes (availability, security, usability, etc.) are mentioned.

This requirement specifies system behavior (functional): how to handle a request when the train cannot stop at the new target (reject and retain old target). It also describes error-handling/failure behavior (fault tolerance) by defining graceful handling of an unfulfillable action. No explicit availability, performance, security, usability, or other non-functional aspects are stated.

Specifies a functional constraint on where the Reversing function can be executed (only in one active cab that remains open during the procedure). This defines system behavior rather than availability, security, or other quality attributes.

Specifies a functional capability ('Reversing shall be possible') and ties it to a parameter ('value given with the MA'). No mention of availability, performance, security, usability, maintainability, etc., so only Functional is set.

This specifies that the driver must be able to use a specific feature (Reversing) without an extra confirmation step—so it defines functional capability. It also implies a usability requirement (reducing required steps/improving ease of use), but does not address availability, security, performance, etc.

Specifies functional behavior (reversing must be supervised to specified distance/speed) and references 'National Values' implying regulatory/legal compliance. No indication of availability, performance, security, or usability concerns.

The statement defines a capability of the system ('distance supervised can be extended from the trackside') so is a functional requirement. The phrase 'can be extended' implies scalability/extendability of supervision range, so Scalability is applicable. No explicit mention of availability, performance, security, usability, portability, maintainability, operability, legal, or look-and-feel.

Specifies a system action (cancel the MA) triggered by a condition (train starts reversing). This is a functional behavioral requirement; it does not explicitly state availability, safety/fault-tolerance, security, or other non-functional concerns.

Specifies a capability/behavior of the train system (automatic handover between RBC areas without driver intervention), which is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly state availability, fault-tolerance, performance, scalability, security, usability, or other NFRs.

The requirement specifies that there shall be no performance penalty (train spacing and speed) during a transition between RBCs when two radios are available — this is a performance constraint (PE). It also implies resilience during handover (maintaining performance despite change), which is a fault-tolerance/resilience concern (FT). No legal, usability, security, availability, or other qualities are explicitly stated.
Requirement describes graceful degradation when only one radio is operational (fault tolerance) and explicitly notes a possible performance penalty (performance).

This statement specifies a system capability (supervise train and shunting movements), which is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly mention availability, performance, security, usability, or other non-functional aspects.

The statement specifies a system capability: trainborne equipment shall monitor movement direction relative to permitted direction to prevent roll away/unwanted reverse movement — this is a functional behavior requirement. It does not explicitly state availability, fault tolerance, security, usability, or other non-functional concerns.

This requirement specifies a system capability to prevent trains from entering routes when criteria are not met (functional behavior) and implies access/control or safety enforcement (security/authorization). It does not mention availability, performance, maintainability, etc.

Specifies a capability (driver can release emergency brake) which is a functional requirement. It also pertains to system operability (operator action/interaction) rather than non-functional concerns like performance, security, or usability.

The requirement specifies observable system behavior about what information may be displayed when ETCS equipment is isolated, which is a functional specification. It also explicitly restricts disclosure of ETCS information, which is a confidentiality/security constraint, so Security is marked. Other quality attributes are not implied.

Specifies a system behavior (isolation shall disconnect ETCS from braking system), which is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly state availability, fault-tolerance, security, or other non-functional concerns.

The requirement specifies a capability the system must provide — receiving information from national train control systems via STM — which is a functional (behavioral) requirement. It does not state availability, performance, security, portability, scalability, or other quality constraints explicitly.

The requirement specifies a system function: displaying or being compatible with national train control system information (functional). It also describes interfacing/compatibility with an external system, matching operability/interfacing concerns (O). It does not state availability, performance, security, portability, UI aesthetics, or maintainability constraints.

This is a functional requirement specifying a capability (allow unfitted operation when ordered by trackside). It does not state non-functional qualities like availability, security, maintainability, etc.
Specifies a functional capability: the system must allow 'Unfitted operation' when the driver selects it at startup. No quality attributes (availability, security, usability, etc.) are implied.
This requirement specifies a system function: the onboard system must supervise/enforce a maximum (ceiling) speed for the train. It describes expected behavior rather than non-functional qualities.

This statement specifies a functional rule/behavior for computing the ceiling speed for unfitted operation (take the lower of two values). It describes what the system should do rather than a quality attribute, so only Functional is marked.

Specifies a functional capability: the onboard system must switch ETCS status when instructed by trackside. No explicit quality constraints (performance, availability, security, scalability, etc.) are mentioned.

States a functional capability of the ETCS on-board system (receiving track description from trackside). No explicit non-functional constraints (availability, performance, security, scalability, etc.) are mentioned.

This requirement specifies a capability of the system — sending adhesion-condition information from trackside — which is a functional behavior. It does not explicitly mention availability, security, performance, operability, or other non-functional aspects.
Defines system behavior: permit driver to change adhesion conditions and specify priority of trackside information — a functional requirement describing actions and rules.

This requirement specifies a capability (sending information) — a functional behavior. It does not explicitly state availability, performance, security, interoperability, or other quality attributes, so only the Functional label is set.

Specifies system behavior (reject movement authority) based on absence of onboard track data—this is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly state availability, fault tolerance, performance, or other non-functional aspects.

Describes a capability the system must provide (sending different speed profiles for train categories) which is a functional requirement. No constraints about availability, security, performance, etc., are stated.

This requirement specifies a functional behavior of the ETCS trainborne equipment (to supervise the end of movement authority when that information is present on-board). It does not state constraints about availability, performance, security, scalability, etc., so only Functional is set.

Specifies what the system shall display on the DMI (target distance) and the rule for deriving it (based on the most restrictive braking curve) — a functional behavior requirement rather than a quality/constraint like performance, security, or usability.

Specifies a functional capability: receiving time-outs associated with movement authority and shortening the movement authority when timeout expires. No quality attributes (performance, security, availability, etc.) are implied.

Specifies a system calculation behavior (compute braking curves from train and infrastructure data with specific inputs/exclusions). This is a functional requirement; it does not state availability, performance, security, or other quality attributes.

This is a data/functional requirement specifying that the ceiling speed level (movement authority) must be defined as a National Value. It primarily describes what data definition/behavior is required rather than availability, performance, security, or UI/operational concerns.

The statement specifies a required system action (request driver acknowledgement before entering an occupied track), which describes functional behavior. It does not explicitly state availability, performance, security, or other non-functional concerns.

Requirement specifies the equipment must be capable of being isolated—this implies operability/manageability (ability to isolate for maintenance/operation) and fault tolerance (isolation for faults/degraded operation). It does not mention availability, security, performance, scalability, portability, legal, look-and-feel, maintainability, or usability explicitly.
Specifies a system behavior: supervising the train based on available speed data. No explicit non-functional constraints (availability, fault-tolerance, safety, UI, etc.) are mentioned.

This requirement specifies a functional behavior/state-transition of the trainborne equipment (remain in Full Supervision until specific conditions occur). It does not mention availability, fault tolerance, performance, security, usability, or other non-functional aspects.

This specifies a system capability: trackside must be able to request driver confirmation before issuing a movement authority (functional behavior). No explicit non-functional constraints (availability, security, usability, etc.) are stated.

This requirement specifies a system behavior (allowing the driver to release the ETCS emergency brake under a conditional rule), which is functional. It does not state availability, fault tolerance, security, performance, usability, or other non-functional qualities.

Specifies a capability/behavior of the ETCS-equipped traction unit (ability to be moved in Shunting without train/track data or movement authority), which is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly state availability, fault-tolerance, security, performance, scalability, portability, maintainability, legal, look-and-feel, operability or usability constraints.

The requirement constrains when a specific system function (transfer to shunting) may be performed (only when stationary), so it is a functional constraint. It also pertains to safe/operational control of the system (restricting operation based on state), fitting operability. It does not address availability, security, performance, portability, maintainability, etc.
This requirement specifies an authorization control to prevent unauthorized use when under RBC control, which is a security (access control) constraint rather than a functional or other NFR.

This requirement specifies a system action/behavior (indicate to the driver that permission was received), which is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly state quality attributes such as usability, security, performance, etc., so only Functional is marked.

Specifies a functional capability: ability to manually select between operation modes (Shunting, Stand By, Full or Partial Supervision). No quality constraints (availability, security, usability, etc.) are mentioned.

Specifies system behavior: automatic transfer to Shunting from particular operation statuses under speed condition derived from trackside information. This is a functional requirement describing what the system must do; it does not explicitly state availability, fault tolerance, performance, security, or other non-functional concerns.

Specifies a required system action (ETCS must request driver confirmation before automatic transition to Shunting). This is a functional behavior requirement; it does not explicitly state non-functional qualities such as availability, security, usability, etc.

This is primarily a functional requirement: it specifies a system behavior (ETCS shall supervise shunting operations to a permitted national speed). It also implies compliance with national permitted speed regulations, so a legal/compliance aspect is indicated. No explicit availability, performance, security, usability, or other quality attributes are mentioned.

This requirement specifies a system behavior/feature: allowing application of the 'train trip function' under a specific condition (shunting movement passing a signal showing 'danger for shunting'). It describes functional behavior rather than availability, security, performance, or other non-functional aspects.

This is a behavioral constraint specifying when the 'Exit from Shunting' function is allowed (only when train is stationary). It defines functional system behavior rather than availability, security, or other quality attributes.
Specifies a functional behavior: system must perform exit from shunting when driver selects that option. No non-functional qualities (performance, availability, security, etc.) are implied.

Specifies a system capability/behavior: how Partial Supervision is selected (by driver or via track-to-train transmission). This is a functional requirement; it does not specify availability, security, usability, or other quality attributes.

Specifies a required acknowledgement action (functional behavior) and a strict time bound of 5 seconds for that acknowledgement (performance/timeliness). No indications of availability, security, scalability, or other NFRs.

This specifies a system behavior: that 'Partial Supervision' must be indicated on the DMI (a display/UI). That is a functional requirement related to the user interface; it also constrains the UI (look-and-feel) by requiring an indication on the display. No availability, security, performance, scalability, portability, maintainability, operability, or legal aspects are implied.

Specifies a system behavior: under Partial Supervision the train shall be supervised based on available speed and distance data. This describes functionality (how supervision is performed) and does not explicitly state non-functional aspects like availability, performance, security, etc.

Specifies a capability/behavior of the train system (to be supervised to a ceiling speed), which is a functional requirement. It does not explicitly state availability, fault tolerance, security, performance, or other non-functional concerns.

Specifies behavior of information shown on the Driver-Machine Interface (functional), and constrains its presentation and interaction (look-and-feel and usability requirement about when/how the value is displayed).

Specifies a system behavior: the train shall leave Partial Supervision under listed conditions (trainborne equipment failure, Shunting selected, or Full Supervision available). This is a functional requirement describing mode-switching; no non-functional qualities are stated.

The statement specifies a capability/behavior the system must provide (ability to order a train trip under the condition of passing a stop signal). It does not explicitly state availability, performance, security, or other quality attributes.

This requirement specifies a system behavior: automatically transferring to Full Supervision upon receipt of movement authority and necessary information via track-to-train transmission. It describes functional logic/triggering; it does not specify availability, performance, security, or other quality attributes.
Requirement specifies a functional capability (supervision of speed and distance). It does not mention availability, fault tolerance, security, performance, usability, or other quality attributes.

Specifies functional behavior (train supervised to ceiling speed) and UI/display requirement (supervised speed hidden on DMI unless driver selects it). This is primarily functional plus look-and-feel; it also affects usability by requiring user selection to view the speed.

This requirement specifies a system function: indicating the supervised shunting speed to the driver upon request. It describes behavior (what the system should do) and does not state availability, performance, security, usability, or other non-functional constraints.

This specifies a capability: on request of the RBC, the driver can confirm that the track ahead is clear—i.e., a functional requirement describing system/user behavior. It does not explicitly impose availability, security, usability, performance, or other non-functional constraints.

Specifies a capability to define locations with behavior (configuring speed increase tied to train front) — this is a functional requirement about system behavior/configuration, no explicit non-functional constraints.
Specifies functional behavior: braking curves must ensure train speed compliance. No explicit non-functional concerns (availability, performance, security, etc.) are mentioned.

Specifies system behavior in response to a detected failure (apply emergency brake to stop train)—a functional requirement. It also explicitly addresses handling of a failure condition (graceful/resilient action), so it implies fault tolerance.

Specifies a system function: how the release speed is to be determined (calculated onboard from sensors/parameters or provided from trackside). No quality constraints like availability, performance, security, etc., are implied.

Specifies a behavioral rule about which speed source takes precedence (trackside over onboard). This describes functional behavior/requirement rather than availability, performance, security, or other NFR categories.
